\s22\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11733749 \rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22\alang1025 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\cgrid\langnp2057\langfenp2057 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Part One: Interview held on 30th June, 1997 [text insertions are from Peter Townsend]
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Can I ask you, first of all, about your grandparents, and whether you remember them, and whether they were important to you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 I came from a very mixed\_
class background in the North of England. I was born in Middlesbrough, as it happened, so I was ... my mother, at the time, having just married, was living in Stockton\_on\_Tees with her mother, my grandmother, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}
Middlesbrough{\*\xmlclose}. And my grandmother was the key figure in my early life, because she was left by her husband, with three small children, in a very tiny terraced house in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Middlesbrough{\*\xmlclose}
, and she took in washing, and she rented out the two rooms upstairs, in order to get by and make a living. S
he was also a woman who was a kind of midwife for the local area, or, at least, worked with the midwife, and there were extraordinary tales sometimes told by my mother of going into a woman's house and finding a dead baby in a box on the shelf of the kitc
h
en. So my grandmother came from a generation where there were large families and many early deaths. And this was near a fishing community. My grandfather's family were fisherfolk, and to this day, I don't know a great deal about them, except that one of t
hem, an uncle of mine, or, rather, a great\_uncle, was a bookie at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Ascot{\*\xmlclose} race course, and there was certainly an element of gambling in that side of the family.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 This is your mother's father you're talking about now?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 This is my mother's father, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 And the village, do you remember which it was? The fishing village?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 This was in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}Durham{\*\xmlclose}
, on the coast, rather than further south around Middlesbrough and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}North Teesside{\*\xmlclose}. My mother was a great singer, and I had a marvellous experience recently of going to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname 
PlaceName}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Middlesbrough{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town Hall{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. [The University of] Teesside knew of my connection to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}
Middlesbrough{\*\xmlclose} because I've written a number of research projects around health in the North\_East, and I went [to receive] an Honorary Doctorate. But the award took place, strangely, on the platform of what used to be 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname PlaceName}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname PlaceName}}Middlesbrough{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town Hall{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, and it was on that same platform that my mother, at the age of 16, sang the lead role in Madam Butterfly. And she became, in her teens, a very well\_
known singer in the town and the surroundings. She was really in amateur dramatics, she was in the Amateur Dramatics Society of that time. She sang in lots of operettas and operas, and that actually led to 
her going on the stage and earning a living from it. She met my father in Stockton Amateur Dramatics Society performances and they sang together, and after she married, they had me a year or so later, and he got a job at the ... at 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Glasgow{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Went t
o Glasgow ... to cut a long story short, my mother left him, with me, came back to join my grandmother in Middlesbrough and, in a sense, I was the child of a lone parent family, although supported very much, and more so, by a grandmother. And then we came
 to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, to Pimlico.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 So how old were you when the marriage broke up?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 I was about a year and a half.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 So you really don't know why all that happened?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 No. Well, I've got my speculations ... more than speculations. I ha
ve heard both sides of it. Both my father and my mother have lived to 90 and 91 respectively. And my mother ... I mean, she tells a different story from my father, about her loneliness and his indifference to her on a number of occasions, and flirting wit
h
 others. Of course, you get that sort of story. He places a lot of blame on my grandmother and the fact that she was very clinging, and that my mother did get lonely, but that she was affronted that he was having a very sociable life, or beginning to lead
 
a sociable life, and she wasn't, and she wasn't having the kind of adulation that she had back in Middlesbrough on the stage. So you get these kind of accounts that I certainly had from the two of them, although I can, to some extent, even now, see both s
ides, although I didn't know everything, of course, about what was going on. I think one of the important things about that time was, of course, that my father, his background I haven't explained. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 My mother's background was one of being brought up in a 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Middlesbrough{\*\xmlclose} - very nearly - a slum. The street is still there, the house isn't, though some of the old houses still are, quite near {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname PlaceName}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname PlaceName}}Middlesbrough{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town Hall{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, as it happens. And she was, clearly, a very active and a very 
talented girl, who didn't really have the education she deserved, and really, showed her skills very much through singing, as soprano. She was very much like the famous Gracie Fields, and in effect, I used to think she sang better than Gracie Fields, but,
 of course, I was prejudiced at the time! And my mother went on, perhaps I'd better just finish this side of the story, my mother went on, when she was in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, we had a very chequered existence, because some weeks she was very much in work, and 
other weeks she wasn't. She tended to live on what money she had, sometimes she had two or three pounds a week from earnings, singing at Clubs and at Masonic Lodges and the Cafe Royal and so on, in London, earning ... This was in the mid\_
1930s, and she was also, she did play quite a substantial role in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 The Girl in a Taxi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 . 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
So she moved from soprano work in opera, to comedienne work, which is both singing and comedy work. And then in the War, at the beginning of the War, she first hit fame, or moderate fame, in a well\_
known musical play called New Faces, but that only lasted a few months because of the War. And then she sought work with ENSA during the War years, like Vera Lynne and others, and she went, toured the country to Army barracks, she went across t
o France and sang to troops there, and she ... the high point of her career came at the end of the War, when she sang in two Royal Command Performances, and I have one of the photos to this day. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 But after that, like a lot of other women, she was not want
ed when she reached her forties, on the stage, and she no longer got phoned up for new commissions. And she just, for a time, collapsed with that. It was a very tragic period for her, and she didn't know what to do, and became morose and depressed, and gr
a
dually, she pulled herself out of that, by getting a job with Shell, as a clerk, and then as a supervisor, in Shell Petroleum. She actually served in BP too, for a time, but that was then her career until she retired in her sixties. She misled Shell about
 her age, she told them ... her date of birth was 1901, but she put a little cross on [the one] to make it 7! And they didn't know they were employing her until the age of 66 instead of 61 or so, when they retired women off, or 60.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 And did she ever remarry?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
No, she didn't. She came from a generation which tended to regard marriage as very ... as a fixture, as it were, even though she was separated, and then later divorced. And she had a partner for some few years, but not for
 many. And I think found some kind of life as a single person. In fact, towards the end of her life, she became what would normally be recognised as a bit agoraphobic, which merely meant that she made a very vigorous life of living alone, and enjoying tel
e
vision and visits from friends and family. And this was her during her lifetime. So you can tell she has been an enormous influence on me, because she has a huge sense of narrative and wit, and regales every audience with most extraordinarily pointed and 
revealing stories about past experience. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
My grandmother was more the sort of stable influence on me, because she provided the meals and looked after the home during the War when my mother went out to work, indeed, my mother was once blown off the platform
 by a doodlebug, in an audience of 500 troops, and was taking risks going around, at that time, to earn a small living. But, as I said, she was up and down, and some weeks we went with very little food, and my grandmother was the stable influence and main
taining the food. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
My father, I'd better just say, very quickly, was ... in the First World War, he flew for the Royal Flying Corps, and he went to some 20 airfields [in France] towards the end of the War. He misled them about his age, told them he was old
er than he was, and yet only flew in the last year of the War, which I think is a good thing, because I'm sure he would have been dead if he'd served any longer. As it was, he was shot down once, and was very fortunate. He regarded that as the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}high point{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 of his whole life, and it's rather sad, because he became a commercial traveller of a kind, for much of the rest of his life. He then joined up again in the Second World War. He was rather amazing, he was one of the few people who served in both Wo
rld Wars as a pilot. He was a training pilot mainly, in the Second World War, for two or three years, and was training, went over to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Canada{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. But service in the RAF, was really the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}high point{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} of his whole life, and it was reflect
ed in what he collected in his home, which was a modest bungalow, towards the end. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
