He was a commercial traveller. He sold, at one time, he sold Sun raisins, and he ... sometimes he had better times than others, but he was usually on relatively short\_
term contracts, meaning that he had to produce a good deal of business, to have continued employment. So he tended to roam the North of England, selling the wares of the companies who commissioned him to do so. I think he p
artly enjoyed that, because he had access to a car and the status that ownership of a car, in those days, in the 1930s, gave people, although his earnings never appeared to be very considerable. He was supposed to give a regular maintenance allowance towa
r
ds my upkeep, of course, and according to my mother, he wasn't very regular. According to him, he was pretty regular. So I don't know what the truth was about that! But it amounted to, at that time, it was of the order of a pound a week, and then it was r
aised to \'a32 a week later on.
