 an absolute rock, in terms of emotional solidity, but there weren't a lot of other ... let's say, domestic distractions. And I remember lots of games alone in the evenings, perhaps when we were not allowed out after dark, or whatever it was, playing game
s
 over the sofa, and I got very caught up in, first of all, lots of lead toys. I used to remember boxing, practising boxing, with the boxing gloves on. Somebody gave me, my aunt gave me a wonderful birthday present at the age of seven, boxing gloves, where
 
I remember hitting the wall with these boxing gloves repeatedly, and that's a big memory. Playing alone, inventing things alone, proceeding, even at the age of 11, to writing and duplicating on one of those roller duplicators with jelly, this very firm je
l
ly, and you used to be able to roll out what you'd written. I produced a school magazine called Bombshell, at the age of 11, and I rolled out the papers with this roller, which you had to ink the jelly, and then place the paper in with a clean roller, and
 roll it over the top, or words to that effect. And I used to do this for hours. I was very capable of doing continuous jobs of that kind, to end up with something worthwhile. 
