I also remember, at that age, another thing which shows the isolation of the single child. The houses, we moved from an attic flat in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}Belsize Crescent{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, where I was at the beginning of the War, where I remember looking out of the window and counting more than 200 barrage balloons across {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}, because we had a wonder
ful view over the whole of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} from that top attic. But because of the bombing, we moved to a basement and ground\_
floor flat, which happened to have ... the seven terraced houses in that row, shared a garden behind them, and in that garden it w
as possible to play cricket, and I remember endlessly bowling, I mean, just literally, for two or three hours at a time, on my own, or playing tennis against a net, endlessly. So there's a mixture, on the one hand, of my having to make out myself, alone, 
in many contexts, but also of being very sociable at school, and really responding to school in a way which many kids wouldn't, because there's so much to attract them at home.
