en I'm talking about, around the turn of the century. There were three children, and one died early of diphtheria, and my grandmother never ... this was the greatest blow of her life, losing a son from diphtheria, at the age of ... he was seven. Her other
 
son, Bill, again, misled about his age in joining up for the First World War. He served in the trenches, was blown up by a mortar, lost both his legs, gradually recovered in hospital, met a nurse, ten or fifteen years older than he was, Emmie, who then ma
r
ried him and looked after him, and they lived in Portsmouth, where he got a job with the Royal Navy, as a kind of office worker. And I occasionally was taken down by my grandmother, to see them. We couldn't afford to do that often. And they had a little A
ustin Seven, which they drove up to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
