{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname PlaceName}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname PlaceName}}Westminster{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname PlaceType}}School{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, and taught the sixth form there, which was where John Freeman was. And after that, he went to the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname PlaceType}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname PlaceType}}University{\*\xmlclose} 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname PlaceType}}College{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname PlaceType}}School{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. He was a very young Headmaster before the War, and 
he was there all through the War, when I was at that school. And he was an extraordinary example of a person who taught not only moral values, but a whole kind of approach to keeping open doors on experiences. He was someone who ... let me give you one ex
ample of how, what an extraordinary person he was. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
He had what he called "Commando Exams", at one point during the War. He decided that stock exams were really not very stretching, that they were ... you know, if you lived in the kind of home which could 
train you for them, and you came from the sort of background that you could, you could perform ... get the orthodox results, and get to university accordingly. But he thought that often boys, because he was teaching boys, had talents which weren't appreci
ated. So he devised the "Commando Exams", where, through the day, we had to indulge in a number of other activities, than all sitting in a quiet environment, writing papers. What he did was, we had to run a three\_mile cross\_
country race around Hampstead Hea
th, and if we did it fast, we then had more time than everybody else to write the maths paper. But if we ran it too fast, and got so exhausted we were incapable of writing the maths paper, so we had to make some judgements about this. We had to swim two l
engths of the swimming bath between exams, too. So we went for a cross\_
country run, we did an exam, we went in the swimming bath. And then there were two or three exams, I remember acutely, where the deliberate intention was to distract us. We were given th
e instruction that we had to concentrate on the paper, but we had a master at the front of the classroom acting the fool, or banging the table repeatedly with a ruler, doing everything to distract us. And so the whole idea was, how could you perform in th
e
 most trying experiences of life? Because performance was generally one where there were environmental interruptions and diversions and distractions. And he tried this. But I thought that was a brilliant idea, and I naturally thought it was brilliant, bec
a
use I did rather well at it, because I wasn't that good among my peers at school. I did well, but not as exceptionally as I had at the elementary school, is the truth. And I was very pleased, because I used to, generally speaking, do very well at sport, a
nd I was also quite good at concentrating when there were distractions around! (LAUGHS) 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
So he was a colossal influence. He also took me - I think, in retrospect, I know he had gay inclinations, but he, he exercised a kind of self\_discipline about that. I 
didn't really appreciate that so much at the time as subsequently, because he committed suicide because of one event, I believe. But, looking back, he, his sensitivity, the way in which he opened people up to the possible creativity of their talent. I rem
ember, he took two or three of us in his car, he was keen on the very early Jaguars, he took us in a Jaguar to the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Surrey{\*\xmlclose}
 hills, and we sat on the top and talked about how we could change the school, as sixth formers. And it was almost like taking, I m
ean, this was very unusual at a school, for a Headmaster to take the senior, most senior boys, for a kind of Awayday, as we would call it now, to say, "Well, what's wrong with the school? What can we do to put it right?" But seriously, that's what he did,
 
and this really stretched us, because we ... so many children, so many schoolboys and girls take it for granted that the environment, and what they are taught, and the way they must behave, are givens, which just have to be accepted automatically, rather 
than thought about. And he taught me to think about values in a very acute way. 
