\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
And my future wife then, Ruth, who I met at the age of 16, and we wer
e very much in love at the age of 17, 18, she ... her mother was a Christian Scientist. Her sister, Jennifer, who was only a year older than her, at the age of 18 or 19 at the time, was also very much devoted to Christian Science. I became interested, I r
e
ad about it, and sort of played along with it, I think is the right phrase, for a year or two. And then there was a tragedy, because just when penicillin had been developed in 1947, Jennifer fell ill with tuberculosis, and because of the Christian Science
 ideology, she allowed herself, and they allowed her, to die. And she died in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Wales{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And I've never forgotten going to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Wales{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} in the last days of her life, and running around the, literally running around the neighbourho
od, to just find something to do while others were crying in the house situation. And that finished Christian Science for life, for me, of course. And it meant that I also, because of the introduction to Christian Science, which I'd played along with, and
 then the discovery that it was so ... in some important respects, yes, it has a lot to say for it, of course, like all religions. 
