I had a very eclectic educational upbringing. Early on I was good at maths. I then discovered my interest in English, and writing, creatively, short stori
es and poetry and so on, I was trying to do that quite a lot in my teens. And went on to edit the University paper, and I wrote quite a lot for it. I also wrote poetry at that time. But in terms of the exams I took, I, because I had quite a good geography
 teacher, got very interested in, believe it or not, geology and then geography. And I took the Higher School Certificate in Geography, and I actually took an Exhibition at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}
 in Geography, and was a runner\_up, who was then offered a place on those grounds, at St. Catherine's College, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. So geography was one of the strands in my sixth form work. The other was art. And the third was French and German, which I read to the equivalent of 'A' level, and proceeded, almost systematically
, to forget, much to my shame! I wish I could have become a good linguist, and I didn't. So those were the subjects I did. But at, I was going to read geography at university, that was my intention.
