{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}England{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, or did you travel with the Army?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
I was three or four months at Yeovil, four months I think it was. And then I was at Blandford for well over a year, Blandford in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Dorset{\*\xmlclose}. And I used to try and get back as many weeke
nds as possible, and hitch\_
hiked back and forth, because I was in love with my, with Ruth, this was just slightly before our marriage. We married in 1948, I may say, quite young. I was still only 20 at the time. She was 21. No, I was 21, I beg your pardon,
 just over 21, and she was 22. And, no, it couldn't have been, it was 1949 we married. That's right. I beg your pardon. And the period in the Army was Yeovil, Blandford, and then ... near {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Glasgow{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, for the Royal Army Education Corps. They wanted me
 to go in for some officer training scheme. I did go in for it, and I did succeed. Oh, it was some great obstacle course in both physical terms as well as mental terms, and was offered a place, but I was scared stiff I would be committed to missing the fi
rst year at Cambridge, so I didn't accept, and succeeded in getting to Cambridge a little bit early, as it happens.
