\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 I had, at the time, and I have now, a kind of love/hate relationship to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. It is, undoubtedly, today, the best university, in the sense of having some of the best results, in terms of research, than any university. There's absolutely no question about that. I sa
y that, because very recently, I served for three years for the Universities ... for the UGC, for selecting staff, candidates, Scholarship candidates, for maintenance grants, overseas student grants, studentships. And there was a huge application from all
 
over the world. And it is my honest opinion that not only did Cambridge and Oxford have an unduly large number of places for these studentships, that had been built up over the years, and the truth is that ... the best, the most, as it were, qualified app
licants, applied to them. And in my opinion, they handled it at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}, far better than at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Oxford{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 and some other places. And I learned that grudgingly, let's say, this recent experience, I mean, because I didn't want to really believe that i
t was quite as professionally competent as it turned out to be. There are other respects in which one would wish to encourage more comprehensive values about university education, I understand. But in terms of, you know, you're living within a system, and
 this is the system, and the people, the most go\_ahead people were applying, and from places like {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname country-region}}China{\*\xmlclose}
, may I say, some extraordinary characters in their forties, with umpteen degrees and research papers to their credit, applying to come into {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. And it was difficult, on academic grounds, to deny them. So this sort of experience taught me that ... it goes right back to it, that there were some admirable qualities to that university education. There was also, of course, the most
 engaging qualities of the Backs and the colleges, and the leisurely demeanour, and life of people outside, working conditions. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 But there was the other {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And the two cities exist today, and could be, and should be brought together more 
than they are, in terms of more access on the part of local population to the University, for example. But there are many other examples, I don't want to go on with that. So I had a love/hate relationship, because at the same time as I was absorbing all t
he benefits of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, I knew there were others who were denied them, and those others, sometimes, were only a few streets away. And it was at the apex of the class system, in some ways, and yet one has that kind of ambivalence in the way we loo
k at things, of ... can that, those sort of skills, that kind of research excellence, be created differently by more universalistic values? 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
I think they can. But it isn't easy to demonstrate that, because those universalistic conditions have not been cre
ated, and on the scale and in the way that you and I would want. So I have that love/hate relationship. I tried to keep both sides of it in mind. But I thoroughly enjoyed it. I enjoyed it in the sociable sense, outside working hours. I mean, preparing for
 
my degree, in other words. I did things which were, I think, interesting to this day. I've still got exercise books, thick exercise books, which I kept, of lectures which were given, and books that I read. I tried to get each book summarised on a single p
a
ge, and although I think I wasn't very discerning, I was a bit descriptive and ... insufficiently directed in my thinking, even today, I think I certainly was doing an extraordinarily conscientious job in preparation for a degree. I also was inspired by o
ne or two people, and completely put off by others. I'll give you two examples. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
I was totally inspired by Bertie Russell, who, in his Emeritus years, was coming to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 to lecture just once a week, on a Wednesday morning, at nine o'clock in the morning, and he had a thousand people in the hall. And I was in the front row, and my future wife and I were sitting in the front row listening to him. He was inspirational too, 
b
ecause I was then a ... a raw reporter on the University newspaper, called Varsity, and we had an amazing experience, only five or six weeks into my first year, where I was a reporter, and I was very proud of myself for reporting in the paper, one week, t
h
at Bertie Russell had been found in Moscow, saying that ... not in Moscow, but talking about Moscow, he seemed to have been saying that the atom bomb ought to be dropped on Russia, as a possibility. And I wrote up this story, repeated the story. It turned
 up in our own press. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
