 influence, because he wasn't really part of the actual course so much. But the big influence on the course itself, was a man called John Wisdom, who was quite extraordinary. He used to come in at nine o'clock in the morning, two or three days a week, put
 
his elbows on the desk, and he'd furrow his brow, and bury his head in his hands, and say ... "I was talking about whether this desk was here last week". And he would, we would be spellbound. You could hear a pin drop, because he was speaking, he was thin
king aloud, and sometimes, of course, it turned out that it was very inconsequential and humdrum. But sometimes, it was very penetrating and thought\_provoking. It was an extraordinary example of thinking aloud. 
