 of other philosophy, who taught in the Divinity School, and we all rushed along to the Divinity School to hear his lectures. And at the start, we got discouraged, because not only did he read every sentence, but he repeated every sentence, so we had time
 
to write it down! And do you know, I was so naive and innocent, that I did that for a whole year. And I look back, and I think that was very revealing of me. Here I was, not only ... I wasn't just raw from school, I'd actually been in the Army. Here, at t
h
e age of 20, here was I, taking down every word of this very ... kind of ... well, it was orthodox ... philosophy, which was not really very penetrating, and that was a very bad experience. I mean, it got me nowhere. I didn't learn anything from it. And h
e
 was a very shy man. For instance, once I plucked up courage, at the end of the lecture, he used to start on the stroke of the hour, and finish on the stroke, may I say. But I plucked up courage once, right towards the end, of asking him a question, and h
e, he couldn't take it. He actually said to me, "Oh, Townsend, I will answer you that next week, when I give my next lecture". Which he did: he read it out when he came in.
