 after the first year in College, when she had digs with a University professor and his wife, we bought a slum, which was due to be demolished, it's now a car park next to the Union Building, I may say! But we, there were a few dilapidated, tiny houses, w
i
thout ... which were very damp, which existed then, near the centre of Cambridge, not far from St. John's College, where we, we actually occupied it for three years, as it turned out, in the end. A year after I left too. But for the first two years were t
h
e second and third years of my degree, and it was a dilapidated little cottage of, really, just one room down and one room up. There was a sort of second room, which was really half a room, you could hardly get a bed in it, and a kitchen which was ... you
 couldn't swing a cat in, downstairs. So it was really one room up and one room down. And I remember covering it with Snowcem, standing on a tall ladder and doing it with Snowcem, and we were there for two years. 
