 be as it is. So I'm saying that the marriage ceremony is something that isn't just revealed by the grandmother or grandfather, it's something that's revealed by the Marriage Certificate, by the way the Registrar of Births and Deaths operates, by the way 
in which the priest operates. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Now, to go and discover that, you can't just use a standard questionnaire, you've got to use different methods of ... and more creative, inventive methods of 
finding out about it, and sometimes tracing, because that can be infinitely rewarding, tracing some of the old ... It's rather like all of us have the experience of looking with enormous fascination at the Deeds of our property, of previous generations. A
nd, "My God, look what happened in 1850! Look what happened in 1900! Do you know, it only cost \'a3
150", and so on. We're all familiar with that experience. But, in fact, it carries an echo, and not just an echo, it's been carried on, because, of course, it is
n't what happened in 1848, or say, 1898, in the case of people's houses, it's how it happened in 1899, how it happened 1900, and so on. The connections are really, they're not leaps over a generation, they are gradually reformulated, year by year, and tha
t kind of consciousness of how the connections are still maintained, and yet have been varied, applies to methodology, it seems to me. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
I used to adopt the idea, and I think this is partly, again, due to the anthropologists ... the early ones that I read, 
that you could find out all sorts of revealing things about a society, about a culture, if you read the poetry of the time, if you looked at the fiction, if you talked with the politicians, yes, of course. And you couldn't do everything, of course, and th
ere's a tendency to have to select all the time, but that's true even of sampling, you have to select, and the way you select can be very influential and important for your results. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Participative observation is certainly a great deal of it, because, I mea
n, let me give you a good example of the method, why participative observation is so crucial in many enquiries. If you did the design of a questionnaire on paper, you say you think you want to raise this matter, this matter, and that matter, there is a se
n
se in which you don't know beforehand, before, unless you actually go through that experience with the person you're supposed to be interviewing, you don't know what their priorities are. They may not put the matter in your order of one, two, three, four,
 
five, six, seven, eight, nine, ten. They may start with nine, and go to six, and so on, in terms of their priorities, of what captures their interest, and their involvement, and their enthusiasm, and what they regard as important. I mean, you may be askin
g some people about housing, or I may be asking some people about housing, and they keep harping on about disability. And you suddenly realise, "My God, I haven't got any questions about disability in my questionnaire!" 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Now, participative observation actu
ally communicates some sense of order into the way in which you can describe society and it's relationships, it allows you to ... yes, you may disagree with all the people you meet, if they think the most important thing in life is money, for example, you
 
may think, "Oh God, I don't agree with that, because they plainly act otherwise". And then you get very interested in the question of opinion being different from, or supportive, of behaviour. All of us can ask people, what would happen if you had your in
c
ome chopped in half? And you can give the answers. But that's not to say exactly how it will happen. Many people whose incomes are chopped in half, they will say, oh, they'll give up going to the cinema, or they'll not pay the TV licence, or something whi
c
h they will sensitively understand is a more conventional response of what people are expected to do. In fact, of course, they'll keep up luxuries and often forego what we would regard as necessities of life, like renewing a pair of shoes, or even giving 
up on certain foods, foodstuffs, rather than give up what they call "life's enjoyments", which is a different way ... it redirects your attention into the word "necessity". 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
So what I'm saying is, to get back to it, participative observation allows you to 
get the kind of sense of priorities as people regard them. And participative observation also allows you to observe, more objectively, behaviour, which also gives you another sense of priorities, and which is very important as a corrective to the original
 assumptions you take to the study. So I find that kind of thing quite important. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
And finally, just to say the range of work, I mean, it's evident from the way I'm reacting, and the benefit I've gained from social anthropology, that one method cannot poss
ibly give you all the answers. If you can indulge in others, so much the better. I mean, for me, being able to talk to, my first piece of major work, talk to the general practitioners who gave me access to the cards of the old people's addresses, that was
 
quite significant, because they saw old age, of course, rather differently, from the people ... let's say, those who were older themselves. And for me to actually visit, because I did go with the Agombars to the funeral of a brother, was an extraordinaril
y revealing experience.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
What I'm trying to say is that it's often a very wise thing, when you embark on a research study, yes, to choose the main instrument, that may be a questionnaire, but to complement it with other methods which you know will, indeed, 
complement it. In the case of the old people I was just describing, it was very important for me, not merely to go and do most, as it turned out, of the interviewing myself, I did it with ... Peter Marris did some of it, a small number of the 200 people, 
I
 think he went to about 40, I can't remember now, exactly, 40 or 50 of the older people. I went to 150 or 160 of them. This was my first major experience of research. And, looking back, I think I did right. People will find when they look at the actual ac
count of the interview, that it wasn't merely ticking off the questionnaire. But I deliberately didn't give, perhaps, as much ... attach as much importance to pre\_
coding as some other people have since, but knew that there was a sense in which it was import
ant to record some of the things people said, and then to code accordingly, on the basis of what they told you, rather than just ask them for one of three or four selected alternatives, in a language which they couldn't do anything about, because you gave
 it to them. It's extraordinarily difficult to adopt a universal language, a universal terminology, and so I tended to use what is best described now as an open interview schedule.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
But having done that, also to recognise that one of the methodologies was t
o try and write out, or type up each interview as it was done. Because not only was I able to remember certain things which I didn't have time to record, but also to select and order it in a way which would easily be accessible afterwards. Everybody knows
 
that if you just simply type up a recording, not only is it almost impossible to read, but it all happens in a somewhat haphazard order, and it's very difficult finding the key themes that you then want to analyse and write up subsequently. And therefore,
 
as we did, we rearranged the interview into a certain order. All I mean is that any interview is designed to collect information on a range of matters, and if one's wanting, for example, in the case of interviewing old people, to have a section about hous
ing, and a section about marital relations, and a section about relations with children, for example, that you ... even though this may crop up in the actual interview in a very inter\_related form, or a back\_to\_
front form, immediately afterwards, if you des
cribe the interview, you can simply follow the order you want, so that you can find it accessible for writing up purposes later on. That's a fairly obvious thing, but I tried to do that, and I also cut out bits from the typescript copy, which I put in par
ticular envelopes for recovery when I got to those chapters. And I found that that's time\_saving too. And people devise these sort of techniques of saving time. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Another important thing which I felt was, yes, it was minor in relation to the whole study, bu
t getting ten old people to keep a diary, and going through the business of trying to persuade and coax them, because that's what it came to, into doing that for seven days, was enormously revealing. Yes, of course, there were some people whose literacy w
as weak, and who don't appreciate that some of the activities of life that they do every day, are so interesting to others, and what they think is only wanted is something very restricted indeed. And that is, itself, very revealing, as we all know.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Were you keeping an ethnographic field\_work diary yourself, or not?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
I wish I had been. I didn't have time. I had the desire to keep a diary. It's true, looking back, I kept a big, I had a big exercise book which ... there are periods of those fiftie
s and sixties when there are certain days which have got interesting accounts of what had happened to me that day, or to others that day, and this is fascinating to me to look back on now. But, quite frankly, we're talking of one or two or three or four p
e
r cent of my time and activities, which is a shame. I'm certainly not one of those diarists. I envy them, I mean, how the Barbara Castles and Tony Benns and Dick Crossmans of this world managed to dictate or keep any kind of diary in such busy lives is qu
ite an intriguing question.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Then when you went to the interview, I mean, when you were sitting there, did you have this interview schedule there, or were you doing it all from memory?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Oh no. I think it's quite important that people ... I thin
k it's valuable to actually say, "Look, you don't mind me doing an interview, do you? I'm trying to collect information about old people and how they feel about a variety of things, and trying to make recommendations which may be helpful so far as the dev
e
lopment of government policy is concerned". I don't know, one conveys that kind of idea as simply as possible, and then, say, "You don't mind if I take a note? I have to do this, because I forget things". And that's perfectly honest! That's true! Except f
o
r the most remarkable people among us, it is true. And people get used to it, I find. I mean, if you're straight with people, and you've not just got a concealed microphone about your person, I think that's much better, and is both open and honest, and th
e
y accommodate to it. I usually find they may be looking at what I'm writing, and "What are you writing that for?" he sometimes says, "I don't want ... I don't think that ... I wouldn't like my neighbours to know that". Then I'd stop, and say, "Okay, I won
't put a word down about that, and I'll only go on when you get back to other things". That very rarely happened. Most people got lost in their narrative, rather like I am now!
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 So once the interview was over, would you then - because you always had s
ome sort of description of the person, didn't you - you did that afterwards?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Yes. Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
And then did you expand the notes that you'd taken, so the typescript was partly from notes at the time, but partly from what you put in afterwards?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Oh yes, I think I ... I think, like a lot of people, I have a good, very short\_
term memory. I mean, if you go and do an interview in the afternoon, and come back in the evening, and dictate it straightaway, not only do you manage to iron out the hesitations, and the blurs, and the half\_
finished sentences and so on, but you do recapture some of the ways they said it. I know it's not perfect, but you get very close to it, and you can actually ... some of the key statements and events, you certainly record in, I think, a reliable way.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Did you take photographs?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
I took some in the streets, yes. One of the facts about that original study was that ... I only wish I'd taken a lot more, may I say, but there were occasionally, and I deliberately 
went round and tried to take some photographs, which I then submitted to Routledge, the publisher, in the hope that they would include 16 or 32 pages of photos. But they said that was going to cost them too much, and they ruled it out. And I now think, I'
m talking now in 1997, I think that, quite frankly, if that book were to be ever re\_
issued, I'd love those photos to be included. I've still got them. And, of course, they're much more interesting now. Because, for example, a common feature of ordinary stre
et life at the time, was not only the way in which people stood outside their doors, leaning on their brushes, and women with aprons on, scrubbing their steps, or cleaning their windows, talking to each other in neighbouring terraced houses, but there wer
e
 things like the "little mothers" wheeling the pram, the "little mother" being the eldest daughter in a family of, say, 12, 13: and because there was still, then, many families of three, four, five, six in them, it was quite common for the eldest daughter
,
 reaching her teens, to then be a kind of mother substitute in certain key activities, like looking after the baby, and wheeling it to the shops, and even dressing the baby indoors. But they took a terrific pride in showing them off to their fellow pupils
,
 or fellow girls, their friends in the surrounding streets, or at school ... "This is my baby", there was a great deal of status in that. It's very much a status symbol, the pram was, in those days ... it was a carriage, rather than a pram, and often buil
t in chrome, and cost a small fortune in working\_class wages at the time, but was one of those symbols of display, which working\_class mothers sought after.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Did you think of using a tape\_recorder at that point?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 I did, and I did use it. I've s
till got a few tapes of some of the most interesting people I went to. Very vivid.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Do you mean you'd go back to them with a tape\_recorder, because you thought they were special?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Yes. I think, at that stage, tape\_recorders were pretty novel. 
They weren't all that good in the way they worked, and, indeed, since then, it's been ... it was a great trial to me even, I mean, as long ago as 15 or 20 years, in the 1970s I tried to get them re\_
recorded on to modern cassettes, for example, and I found 
that two or three of them were on tapes which couldn't be without an enormous difficulty, and I still have two or three which, I was told, it would be enormously difficult to reproduce in cassette form. And, no doubt, there is the technical possibility of
 re\_doing them, which I'm going to look into. But I don't have many, I have to confess. I did that only subsequently on a few occasions. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
I've probably got a dozen recordings, covering, perhaps, 15, 20 hours of recorded interviewing. But it was subsequent 
to the main thing, partly done because I had the intention of doing a chapter or two on changes over two or three generations, because I was speaking to elderly people in the mid\_
1950s. Of course, quite a few of them went back to the 1880s and 1890s, and could tell me about events then which weren't recorded, and, you know, this is a kind of oral history. I only wish now that - I mean, that was a more policy\_
related aspect of the work I was doing, and I sometimes look back and think that - perhaps the emphasis of work tended to be a little too biased towards the policy\_related, rather than to -to exhuming, if that's the word, distant social reality.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 But I think it's fair to say that you had a feeling for wanting to give a voice to the people, because 
I remember you having that attitude.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 And so, in a way, its quite interesting that you didn't use a tape\_
recorder, and I don't think anybody doing your kind of work, was using one then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Of course, it's very difficult to do it. I 
mean, it's an easy thing to do, in a sense, you think you've got it all on tape, and you have. But, my God, if you get back home, and you've done a hundred interviews, and you've got 500 hours of tape, or 300 hours of tape, the problem of selection is fan
tastic, without taking up the same amount of time looking for the things that you wanted, and then having to re\_
repeat them. I think, still, the best plan, even if you record, and I've tried to do this myself a few times, if you record an interview, to be a
bsolutely punctilious about what was said, so that you could, with your hand on your heart, say, "This isn't recollected afterwards, but this is actually what they said", then the ideal is to, even when you've heard a recording, to go back home and then t
a
ke another half hour, in your own way, repeating what you think were the key points that were expressed during that interview, and then I think there's more possibility of getting back to those interviews which were particularly revealing, and important f
or you to illustrate.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Now, I think this is very interesting ... I also wonder whether - and you can say yes or no - is it true that you wanted their voices to be heard? That, when yo
u present the book, for instance, the people come out as individuals saying things in words, don't they?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Where do you think you got that idea from?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 That's perceptive of you to note that. I think it's partly to do with a great
 ... Anything we do in methodology, can be set out at quite considerable length, with some sensitive qualifications and alternatives. I think that's true of any particular method of work, of how we proceed. And one of the things that struck me, and I'm no
t
 sure I did it all that well, it's difficult to convey, is that I was struck by the fact that when people gave quotations in books, from interviews, much turns on how you weigh the importance of that, in terms of who said it, and in what circumstances, an
d
 what kind of person they were. And so I adopted the technique of feeling that it would be better to have fewer quotations, instead of having two or three lines every so often, let's say, to have a longer passage, but to precede that with three or four li
nes, which made it absolutely crystal clear to the reader, what kind of person was saying this, from the sample that you'd interviewed. 
\par 
