of the person, and tend to remember some of the critical views. Peter was, partly because he joined forces with Michael in the early years, to write the first book, Michael depended on him terribly for producing the goods. But equally, I think Peter neede
d
 to rely on Michael for ideas and direction, and, therefore, it was a good combination, in some respects. But it meant that Peter was always, himself, uncertain of the value or the originality, or the ... the searching nature of his contributions. And I t
h
ink Peter Marris and I, whether we like it or not, were ... more intellectually creative. Whether we were right or wrong, is another matter. But, given the background that we had, the kind of authority which, to some extent, I have to say, a degree in phi
