But in his early period, he was absolutely crucial in the response in helping to formulate, first of all, what was then known as the Guillebaud Report. This was a report that was prompted by Conservative concern that expenditure on the National 
Health Service was getting out of hand \_
 a rather familiar story, I may say! But at that time, it was absolutely crucial to try and scotch this impression that had been created, and was being fostered by Conservatives, for the very good reason that they ha
d opposed the nationalisation of the Health Service. And as it was then only in it's very early years, let it be noted, having started in 1948, it was quite important to give it time to consolidate, and to give it resources to consolidate and to become su
c
cessful. Brian was the inspiration of the report that he and Richard drew up, which was virtually adopted lock, stock and barrel, in this report, and they also produced a separate book for the Cambridge University Press, of a very high order of analysis o
f
 the development of the British National Health Service. And this was a tremendous initiative, which I think, literally, secured the Health Service for another twenty years or more, before other rumblings began developing. So, on that alone, I would rate 
him very highly, may I say. 
