But he also, secondly - and it may seem interesting to you that I almost know more about what his contributions have been than I know about Richard, even though the difference in the publicity of the two has been so marked. His
 second contribution was a kind of background historical analysis of different aspects of health. He did a brilliant book called }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 The Hospitals}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 . The majesty of it is quite breath\_taking, because few people have the daring to look over an entire ... well, ge
tting on for two centuries, and to give the first account of the growth of hospitals within British society \_
 voluntary hospitals, private hospitals, and then local authority, and then State hospitals. And this was, still is, the classic work on the evolution of hospitals in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname 
place}}United Kingdom{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. He also did a brilliant book on nurses, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 The History of Nursing}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
, and that was a remarkable account. He meant to do a third book on general practice, but as far as I'm aware, he hasn't yet achieved that. So as a figure producing an almost breath\_
