\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Let's continue, then, with Brian. Maybe you could explain about his earlier life and where he came from.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
He was drawn from the aristocracy. He was, at the time I first got to know him, he was -I think it was 27th in line to the throne. And the Abel\_
Smiths are a very kind of - posh family, and I've heard, I've been with him when he's met the odd cousin in the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname State}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Savoy{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 or the Ritz. And he refers - he used to refer to all of that in a very embarrassed tone of voice, as if he'd cut adrift from it. And, quite frankly, he did cut adrift from it, in deliberate ideological or academic terms, because at 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Winchester{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, he became, he became a Socialist, basically. And he was always very diffident about his aristocratic origins. He was a very 
bright intellectual who had been privileged in the way in which he had access to education. He also had money, because he ran, in his spare time, during the period I've been speaking of, an organisation called "Just Men", which sold fashionable clothes fo
r young men, and was quite a famous shop in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and had, I think, two or three branches.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 He hadn't started that, though, had he?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 He started it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 He started it, yes. And during this period, I think the most important thing to say about Brian Abel\_
Smith is that he could easily have been, and would have been, in my humble opinion - although one's being, perhaps over\_bold in making such a statement - c
ould easily have been Chancellor of the Exchequer in a Labour Government. It so happened that he was a very close friend of "Daddy Dalton" as he used to call him, Hugh Dalton, of whom Ben Pimlott has written a fine biography. And 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}Dalton{\*\xmlclose}, on his intending retirement, virtually asked Brian if he would allow his name to be submitted as {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}Dalton{\*\xmlclose}'s successor in, I think, it was Blyth, 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Durham{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, which had the biggest Labour majority in the country. And I remember sitting nights with Brian, in his fla
t, which, incidentally, to give another aspect of his extraordinary character, he tried to make his flat very modern, and one way of making the flat very modern was to stick egg boxes to the ceiling, all over! And I remember sitting with him and Tony Cros
l
and, sprawled in armchairs, arguing about pensions, I think, was one of the occasions. But another occasion, when I was with him on his own, we debated, and he really took me into his trust, and really talked about whether he should enter Parliament or no
t, having already had quite a marked success as a young man in analysing social policy. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid15942912 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
The main reason he didn't allow his name to go forward, and in my opinion, he would have been a certainty as a Labour MP - and, quite frankly, given his subsequent his
tory, he could easily have become one of the leading lights of the Treasury, if not the Chancellor. It was really because he was homosexual that he decided not to risk - what he observed had happened to others, the publicity and dreadful tragedies affecti
n
g homosexuals who were found out in public life at the time. This is a great tragedy, speaking in 1997, because, of course, we now accept the fact that there are Ministers of State, women and men, who are lesbian or homosexual. And had public opinion been
 of the kind it is now, perhaps he would have not have decided not to stand for political office. That's a fascinating feature of him. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid15942912 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Why I say he could have been Chancellor of the Exchequer is ... there are a number of reasons. Subsequently he showed, a
s an economist, how much he could contribute to thinking about National Superannuation, pensions, social security. That was certainly true. He showed how - I think he's the foremost world expert on the costs of the Health Service. He wrote several books a
b
out the cost of the Health Service in different countries. He was Treasurer of the Fabian Society for 20 years or more, and kept its books in good order. I mean, he was doing a number of jobs which showed his authority and his incisiveness, and his judgem
ent as an economist. And I think, therefore, that it makes a good case for my belief that he could have been in that sort of high office.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
