 for Barbara Castle, for David Ennals, because he was their political adviser. I had hoped to write }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Poverty in the UK}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
 jointly with him, and he backed off, because, in 1968, he became adviser to Richard Crossman. So there was this element of the great facilitator. And, of course, he then fitted into the Civil Service role like this. 
