What I haven't conveyed yet was what I promised earlier on, was a quick insight into some of the private Homes. And I think it's important to say here that, on the
 whole, the most sensitive behaviour from staff and the most comfortable experiences of residents were to be found in the voluntary Homes. I'm thinking of some Homes run by the Methodists, for example, Methodist Homes for the Aged. This wasn't true of The
 
Little Sisters of the Poor, they were a little bit more like Poor Law institutions, and I remember the men being separated from the women, and it being very difficult to get from one to the other, even at the age of 85, and the men all, because they were 
favoured by the nuns, all got a glass of beer on Sundays, I believe it was. And they were fascinating institutions in themselves. 
