That, of course, is an extraordinarily important point to make, because generally, one of the faults of the residential Home for elderly is, of course, that people of the same age are stuck together, and apart from possible visits, which, for too many, ar
e
 deliberately kept relatively rare, the exchanges between the generations are not many, and it's a kind of artificial community. People try to talk about it being a community, but if the staff don't talk much to the residents, as they don't, apart from a 
f
ew exceptions, and the elderly themselves have come from different localities, and they're often in very different physical circumstances, and have had very different jobs, it's not easy to make close friends. And the number of close friends is relatively
 small, I'm sorry to say. 
