It was like going to a seaside boarding house, which has got not merely unpretentious, but really rather miserable facilities. And some of these places 
where the proprietor had begun to fail to attract tourists or visitors in the season, turned to running a private Home as a more secure alternative to raise money. And these places didn't get enough supervision and regulation, and the local authorities tu
r
ned a blind eye, because it meant that if these places were closed down, more pressure would be put on the local authority alternative. And so there were all kinds of reasons why very bad, very poor places were tolerated at that time. And I think it's tru
e now, probably even more true now with the growth of numbers of private Homes with too little supervision and standards of training and qualifications for staff. So these were the kind of places that we visited.
