s the quotation from the National Assistance Act [that] the residential Homes were needed for people, were required for people "in need of care and attention". So it seemed to me obvious that if we were going to pronounce on the development of these place
s
, were they really providing for people "in need of care and attention"? And it was quite obvious to me that a number of the residents, quite a lot of them, in fact, were not in need of care and attention, that either they had recovered from an episode of
 malnutrition in their own homes, let's say, or from a minor stroke where people thought they were never going to get any better and they did. 
