her because a landlord had his eyes on possible profit, and this is a very important point to make, or because relatives were finding it increasingly difficult to visit, perhaps because they were coming from a long distance, or perhaps neighbours moved, o
r
 relatives had to move. You sometimes get this with sons or daughters who have children and they can't get a bigger flat through the local authority, they have no preference, they have to go to the end of the waiting list, and then they get offered a plac
e
 six miles away, ten miles away, and so off they go, and the elderly person is left high and dry. Yes, they try to get back, but on a very low wage, getting back frequently isn't that easy, especially if there are young children to take to school. So, wha
t I'm trying to say is that, for a variety of reasons, the infirmity of some of the people admitted to residential Homes was exaggerated, as it is today. 
