That instrument, therefore, tied up with both explanations, scientifically, but also policy, as well. And that measure of incapacity for self\_
care, I'm pleased to say, was taken up in all sorts of places, overseas as well as in this country. It led eventually to - you can trace the steps - a lot of others contributed to this particular sequence of steps in modelling and improving and va
rying that kind of method. But it did end up with an international classification of disability, in a functional way, rather than in a medically originated way. Too often, throughout our recent history, disability has been defined in terms of the type of 
d
isability - people who had suffered from cerebral palsy, for example - and not in terms of what they could and couldn't do. And disability mustn't just be discussed only in terms of its medically appropriate origins, or medically classifiable origins, but
 
in terms of it's functional [impact] the state in which people are placed in terms of their capacities or incapacities. And that led to an international classification which has been used quite frequently, and is still used in policy. You've got the Disab
ility Living Allowance, and you've got the Incapacity Benefit, each of which are [based on it]. One can criticise them ... 
