There was a lot of scaremongering going on at that time - as there is now, you know, today there's been talk of the pensions time bomb, for example - but even at that stage, in the fifties and si
xties, in Britain, there was a lot of talk, a lot of crisis talk, as I think it might be described, about the burden of the elderly and the difficulties of their care. And it was quite obvious to anyone examining the situation - [as with the] residential 
H
omes I was looking at, where, as far as I could see, there was really quite a strong case for withdrawing from having too many of them, which were extremely costly, and as I've tried to say, not very successful for the residents themselves - that what peo
p
le most wanted was to be able to continue as long as possible in their own homes, and only in the final analysis, as it were, when they required nursing and medical care, would they grudgingly and reluctantly admit there was a case for them going into a h
o
spital for the chronic sick, or for geriatric patients. And I tended, because of the experience of that research, I tended to take the view that we therefore had to become a more civilised society. And, in fact, also one with a better sense of planning, e
conomically. 
