study of nursing Homes in this country. At the time, nursing Homes accounted for a very small percentage of the elderly population. I think it was under 20,000 beds that we managed to trace, throughout the country, and that number has grown enormously, pa
r
tly under governments which have been determined to try to defray the costs of caring for long periods for elderly people in hospital, and to try to get that covered by private institutions. But, in a way, that is still a pioneering study which shows the 
i
mportance of looking in the round at the functions and at the work of nursing Homes. And even in terms of getting answers to questions put by post, and visiting a few [nursing homes] which we did, almost accidentally or by the way, we formed a fairly stro
ng view about the problems that existed among private nursing Homes. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
