There were two big problems. One was that many of them were very small and they could be run in a very authoritarian way, with very few extremely vulnerable patients in them, with only o
ccasional visits from relatives, and it's very clear that you have to have very high standards of training and management if these Homes are to do the job which we suppose they are going to do. And, quite clearly, some of those in charge, most of them, of
 
course, are matrons, had very few qualifications at all. We did discover that a number of them were, effectively, failed nurses, who had failed within the National Health Service or in large hospitals, and who had been unable to continue their work there,
 
or had been, effectively, persuaded to resign, and who were making a living. There were others who were quite cynically lining their own pockets. Because, of course, vulnerable people, perhaps with a fair amount of income and wealth, don't have much choic
e
 once they're 85 or even 90, and heavily dependent, and often, perhaps, confused in those situations. So, quite clearly, society has an interest, has a stake in ensuring that people in charge of these small places dotted around the country, are of the rig
ht standard. 
