t
here may be a huge difference from big places with several hundred beds, down to places with only four, five, six, seven beds, with patients, or residents, in them. And in sampling those, in order to get reasonable representation, you have to take a much 
h
igher proportion of the very large institutions, because there are very few of them, and a much smaller proportion of the very small institutions which are dotted around the country, and where you may only need to take one in twenty, or one in ten, in ord
e
r to obtain, so long as you do this at random, in order to obtain reliable information about the total. It's also extremely difficult to carry out those particular enquiries because, of course, although it's possible to send postal questionnaires and get 
