I don't want to imply that everything we [researchers] do in life is to discover what are the problems, rather than to also try to understand how success can be achieved unde
r difficult circumstances, and quite unexpectedly. There's almost more pleasure in discovering why that [success] happens than why problems arise. But the pleasures of doing it were that it was fulfilling something that was very ambitious, something that 
was comparatively rare, conducting a national study with a small team, and, therefore, doing it in some depth, rather than doing it very superficially, that gave an enormous sense of pleasure. 
