It's very hard to, long after the event, to give a fair assessment of different colleagues. But we shared a large number of values and 
interest, and I think, a deep commitment to the study itself. And I think I look back, and I'm sure Brian would have said the same, that we were extraordinarily lucky in the people who agreed to join us, each of whom has gone on, I may say, in their diffe
r
ent way, to very high achievements in academic research and teaching. And yet I think, for each of them, in their different way, they went through a very considerable period of difficulty, one or two of them for longer than others! And this illustrates th
e
 problem for all of us, of doing, let us say, considerable research. I think many of us can get into the foothills, few of us can ascend the peaks! And what I've learned is [the importance of] patience with people, and a kind of recognition that you can't
 expect people to be robots, or all designed to the same formula, they can achieve excellence in different ways. I suppose that constantly comes up as a surprise. 
