Now, I also learned, by that process, that I shouldn't behave like Michael Young did behave. If he made the corrections, then the author should automatically accept them
, by virtue of the hierarchy of power. I learned then, and I hope I've stuck to that principle ever since, that if, as a manager, or as a director, or in whatever other capacity one approves or corrects other people's work, that if you really want them to
 
shine, then you have to do it in a spirit of saying, "This is the suggestions I make. I've done them very quickly. You may, in the goodness of time, think they're unnecessary or wrong. You must decide what you want to accept, or whether you want to accept
 some alternative version. It's up to you." 
