Yes. This is reflected, I think, in my work all along. But I came to appreciate, even more strongly, the importance of arguing that the study of poverty was a scientific exercise and
, therefore, different types of social scientists had a lot to convey, and this should be taken very seriously by governments. So if it was scientific, it was therefore also international, and it couldn't possibly be merely national or merely cultural. An
d that opened up many possibilities, and changed the perspectives on how research ought to be done. 
