\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10583505 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
I formed the view, for example, that although one might have to argue at great length about the standards of comparison, that, essentially, one had to have
 a conception of the subject, which was multi-national, and that, therefore, could be operationalised, which would indicate that there was at least a core of criteria which could be used as much in Kenya or India as in the United Kingdom. And I hold to th
a
t view. What requires to be shown is how that core of genuinely comparative, or comparable meaning, can be worked out to sufficient satisfaction of scientists, but also of governments. It could be politically very threatening, just as it could be scientif
i
cally inspirational. I think it's going to be up to others to continue this process to bring it to proper fruition, because it is, this set of ideas is still half-formed, it's still so controversial, that there are many opponents. What we have been, when 
I
 say "we", what we have been trying to do, and I mean by that a few people with whom I've been working in recent years, during the late 1980s and 1990s, has been to encourage, actively, people in other countries to see what can be done to apply in those c
ountries similar methods to that we've used in the United Kingdom. But also to try to get international backing for what might be crudely described as an "International Poverty Line". 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid10583505 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
The most important example of this, in my view, is the United Nations World Summit at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Copenhagen{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 [in 1995], where an Agreement was published subsequently, on social development, which was a programme of action. There are a lot of interesting things about it, but included in it, was the first international recognition
 that absolute poverty and overall poverty, as two somewhat different conceptions of poverty, both applied in every country in the world, rich or poor. And that studies of those two, we might call them levels of poverty, or ideas of the meaning of poverty
, that studies of them should be carried out, and it was agreed by 117 countries who signed up to this Agreement, that this would be carried out. Speaking in 1998, only three or four countries have so far embarked on studies here, and I am referring to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname country-region}}Ireland{\*\xmlclose}, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname country-region}}Denmark{\*\xmlclose}, the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Netherlands{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}. There maybe one or two others that I'm unaware of. The problem is that - and this applies to many international reports - exhortation sometimes isn't followed through. This applies to a lot of human rights questions, of course. 
