If we just give one simple example for this country, you cannot produce an acceptable idea, definition, of absolute poverty, without including some people in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Britain
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. You can immediately think of the homeless. If you walk around {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname PlaceName}}Waterloo{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname PlaceType}}Bridge{\*\xmlclose}, or parts of 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}Manchester{\*\xmlclose}, or {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, people sleeping rough, in parti
cular, but also some of those who are in remote rural areas, you can find cases. They may not amount to very large numbers of thousands of people in some countries, who, by any standards, are living in absolute poverty. But it makes sense to at least try 
to address this cross-nationally. Because there are situations in densely-packed Western societies, which are even worse, maybe, than some of the rural poverty in the poorest countries. I'm thinking of visits to waste ground around tower blocks in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname State}}New York{\*\xmlclose} or {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Chicago{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 where those conditions are far worse, in many respects with empty bottles and drug needles littering ground that hasn't even been cleaned, or gathered in the refuse collection. There are conditions which are really far worse than m
any that are described as impoverished in, let's say, {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Bangladesh{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. This is only, I know, a seminal example, but we need to be humble enough to accept that there are conditions which are unacceptably absolute in a number of rich countries, and indeed, those instances are, in fact, beginning to grow. 
