I think the importance of an International Poverty Line can be expressed in another way, of taking those two standards, and taking them very seriously, in a sense I have to say that is, I thin
k, practical. I think it's very helpful in bringing rich and poor countries together. It makes a lot of sense because, in one way, we can look at absolute poverty and say, "Well, that's a kind of more traditional view, which looks at physical needs, very 
s
eriously, material needs for food, shelter, clothing, fuel". Yes, you have to add some social questions of communication and health and education as well, that's now recognised. But overall poverty, the wider view obviously includes - as I've laboured the
 
point elsewhere a lot - must refer to people's social needs in terms of their obligations as workers, or as family members, and all sorts of other contexts where people will often use their resources to keep their children going, let's say, [rather] than 
s
atisfy their own hunger. But, having said that, therefore, you pursue those two ideas of the measurement of poverty, and you can pursue them in every country. And why they're becoming so much more important is that, in some senses, the divisions, geograph
ically, are becoming very different from what they used to be. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
