I do take, very seriously, the idea that the differences between rich and poor, in every country, are now going to become very much more severe than the differences, on average, between the po
pulations of different countries. That's overtaking social science, it's overtaking academia. The idea of globalisation, I've watched in the last three or four years, in the late 1990s, the growth of, the enormous, almost explosive growth of books on glob
a
lisation. You can put this in all sorts of different ways, but inequality within countries is becoming the dominant problem, rather than inequality between countries. It doesn't mean to say the inequality between countries is going away. Of course it stil
l exists, of course it's a dimension of the whole structural observation as well as agenda for solution, but we have to look at recent trends. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
