en cultures or countries is all very well, but it doesn't really help us to understand why, in the, let's say, the ranking either of countries, or the dispersion of living standards within countries, among a population, how these change so, quite signific
a
ntly, over very short periods of historical time, over 10 or 20 years. I mean, as in this country, how inequality, the polarisation of the population has grown so fantastically in a period of only 20 years. I don't think that shows many signs of changing.
 Indeed, the latest evidence is that it's been developing also in a number of other European and middle-income countries.
