hat's up to them". Or, "It's up to International Agencies", when, in fact, in both contexts there is something that Britain can do, of a major kind, about both poverty in our own territory and poverty abroad. So what I'm trying to suggest is that the way 
i
n which the subject has evolved in, let us say, institutionalised form in a country, there's very close examination, and it's very interesting the way in which misconceptions are almost deliberately perpetrated, or reproduced, from one decade to the next.
 
