\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Yes. This was partly on the same lines as the idea about wider assessment. The kind of short question and answer system of ordinary exams is one thing, and the way you prepare for that, and you think about that, an
d the way that influences your intellectual approach to subject matter, conditions you into, I think, superficiality, in some senses. Whereas if you\rquote 
re expected to choose a subject and then work on it for several weeks, or a few months, even as an undergraduate, to do a project this was relatively unknown. I wouldn\rquote 
t say it was not attempted beforehand, but it was certainly relatively new, as far as I remember, that for undergraduates to be given a project to do, was very rare indeed, if not [unprecedented]: even if it had existed, I can\rquote 
t remember. [But] often I\rquote m well aware that new ideas, [which] you think are new ideas, have really been tried somewhere else.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 There was a staff appointment of somebody who was responsible to help the students, the Project Officer I think?

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 That\rquote 
s right. This was an idea which, unfortunately, Albert Sloman dropped after a few years, that we had two people who were paid by the University. May I say, [how] unprecedented this was. The way we sold it to the Vice-Cha
ncellor originally, when there were very few staff, and when he couldn\rquote 
t resist the argument (LAUGHS), was that this was really like the Sciences, where we needed laboratory assistants who had to be appointed and given tenure. And so we needed Project Offi
cers, people who were appreciative of the fact that Sociology was a skill, that research into it was a great skill, and that advice had to be given about the way in which visits of observation, research interviews, group interviews, etc., were conducted. 
That had a lot of specialised qualities, and that we needed people to be technicians to teach some of the approaches to that. And that was an extraordinarily good move which, I think, established the idea, but it wasn\rquote 
t sustained by the University. What happened was, we reverted, like other universities, into research foundations and other organisations giving money for particular projects, and therefore, the business of overseeing people\rquote 
s new research assistants introduction to the conduct of their research skills was neglected, and still is neglected.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 But that was also in relation to the student projects, wasn\rquote t it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Looked after undergraduates as well as graduates. Yes, you\rquote 
