\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Yes. But it would have inevitably - because pensions is such a large ingredient of social security, it would be extended to affect everything else too, including lone parents\rquote 
 benefit, and disability benefit, sickness benefits, and the whole treatment of low pay, and what could be done during a period of full employment. It would have been marvellous to have got it insti
tutionalised at that stage, a much more socially sensitive set of institutions than we were left with by the 1970s. 
