 State were setting in. After all, what had happened was that after the War, in 1945, great hopes were placed in the Labour Government, which was going to transform society, and to some extent that\rquote 
s still true that it did happen. The big steps on the soci
al front, apart from maintaining largely full employment, or by accident maintaining full employment: we did have the National Health Service, we did have National Insurance, and we had the complete recasting of welfare services. Later, education. And man
y people thought, \'93Oh, poverty\rquote s ended\'94. In the mid and late 1950s, doubts began to surface. There were, and I could go through all these, I\rquote 
ve been through them in some places, the various reports appeared about lone parents, about disabled people, about large families, for example, about pensioners, that made people think, \'93Oh well, that didn\rquote t quite beat poverty\'94
. There were still \'93pockets\'94, that was the word frequently used, there were \'93pockets\'94 of poverty. Then we began to appreciate that, depending on what we meant by poverty, it was really very much larger still, that 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Britain{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}\rquote s inequality, compared with 1938, hadn\rquote t been as materially altered as had been supposed. 
