\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 No. It was formed under it\rquote 
s own steam, but with a grant from ... I think it was Alan Sainsbury, beg your pardon! So it was a Sainsbury indirect financial support [owing a lot to the advocacy of Harriet Wilson, one of the Quaker Social Work founder members] which got us off the
 ground; and we then built on that by making applications here, there and everywhere, for money, and then getting members. And to this day, Child Poverty Action Group depends, in large measure, upon the welfare rights handbooks that it prepares and sells,
 and makes a small profit on, and that has always been the backbone of it\rquote s finances, though, of course, it has had money from the Astor Foundation, from Rowntree and from other sources.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 And how important is the membership?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Membership has always been relatively small. We\rquote 
re talking, I think, in the region of three or four thousand. But it\rquote s a kind of activist membership, and on the whole, there have been 12 to 25 branches, of that order, through the years, in different parts of the country. So
me branches run almost as semi-independent organisations with their own local publicity and local pamphlets and local Advice Centres, which open from time to time. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
The Child Poverty Action Group used to have stalls, which it opened here and there in market streets, and people came to hear advice from somebody perched under an umbrella, like myself. I remember doing it in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}
Colchester{\*\xmlclose} for several years with Adrian Sinfield and others. And that was also a very satisfying thing to do. To do something first-hand is a very good way of enabling you to perceive priorities. I found that too. I\rquote 
ve said that in the past to you about research and interviewing, that people who write up a major piece of empirical research really have to soil their hands in it, in some respect, because otherwise it\rquote 
s very hard to be sure which are the most reliable parts of the enquiry, and what are the most revealing and representative and significant. Unless you have that direct contact and that personal involvement, it seems to me 
very hard to take confidence really in the justifiability of your conclusions, especially if they are contrary to public stereotypes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890122\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 And then you\rquote ve explained how you eventually had a very heavy involvement because Frank was ill. But you carried on involvement, actively, with Child Poverty Action Group for how long?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Oh, it\rquote s very straightforward. There was Tony Lynes for three or four years, th
ere was Frank Field for ten years heading the Child Poverty Group, then there was Ruth Lister, and after Ruth - [there was Fran Bennett] - then Sally Witcher who\rquote s the last Director, who\rquote 
s now just been replaced [by Martin Barnes]. But in 1989 I decided that since I was involved very much in terms of time with both the Child Poverty Action Group and the Disability Alliance, that it had come to a point where, although I don\rquote 
t think I\rquote d overstayed my welcome, or that there were others eager and willing to tak
e over, but I decided that, to really be of some continuing use, I'd better choose between the Child Poverty Action Group and the Disability Alliance. And I resigned, or retired, rather, from the Child Poverty Action Group after 25 - let me get it right, 
after 20 years as Chairman, in 1989, and was then, I\rquote m happy to say, invited to become President. Which I have been since, and therefore am still very much involved in what they\rquote re doing, although I\rquote 
m not in any day-to-day sense. I still write occasionally for the journal. I still go to meetings, and sometimes speak at meetings. But I decided that since it was going through a rocky patch at the time, that I\rquote 
d better stay with the Disability Alliance, and I\rquote ve now been Chairman of the Disability Alliance since 1973, now 25 years.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
So the role of the Chairman, though, is not so much a hands on one. You presumably were lobbying, and continue lobbying, but what else were you doing as Chairman?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Let me go through it. There were four, let us say, four,
 five Executive Committee Meetings in the year; there were, oh, ten, twelve Sub-Committee meetings which the Chairman was obliged to attend, especially the Staff Pay meetings, which I remember with unease and discomfort mostly! Money raising exercises, go
i
ng to see people, write for people. There were strategic statements about the development of policy. There were Annual Reports too, the Annual Meeting which I normally had to manage and speak at, lots of bits of writing all over the place, both about the 
c
auses, and the issues. And Branch Meetings, occasionally went to speak at Branch Meetings up and down the country. It all adds up to quite a heavy involvement. And, of course, recruitment. I mean, to be the chair of staff who were newly appointed. I think
 that covers most of the kind of activities of a reasonably [active] working Chairman, or Chairperson of an organisation.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 And apart from Frank, whom we\rquote ve mentioned, I think it may be worth saying a word about Ruth.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Ruth Lister was a student at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Essex{\*\xmlclose}
, with both of us, in 1970. I think that\rquote s when she graduated, roundabout then. And I knew she was interested in social policy and families, and deliberately went out of my way to suggest that she apply for a research campaigning role, researc
h officer role at the Child Poverty Action Group. I think she was the first who strictly occupied that particular post, that we raised money for. And what she did was to steer the preparation of research pamphlets and write quite a bit herself in the way 
o
f research pamphlets, and really give the Director a considerable amount of back-up. I think, in the early years, Frank Field was rather apologetic about her, and felt that she had all sorts of difficulties, but I think he exaggerated the difficulties, be
cause when, in fact, she took over as Director, she did the job better than he did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3890122\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Should we then switch to the Disability Alliance? So what were the origins of that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Well, listeners and readers are bound to be aware that when you get involv
ed in an organisation you care about, it matters and it sticks with your personality throughout life, and this time the Disability Alliance was really very much a product at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Essex{\*\xmlclose}
, with a close colleague and then friend, Alan Walker. We were very well
 aware in the early 1970s, of the failings on disability policy, and Alan had written about the elderly with me, and, in fact, contributed one or two of the drafts, substantial drafts, to Poverty in the United Kingdom, at that time. He was a very young gr
aduate from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Essex{\*\xmlclose}'s Department of Sociology, and I offered him the opportunity of working as a part-time research assistant, part-time until later we were able to increase the assignment. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 And he and I got into lots of exchanges about disability, part
ly because it was in vogue at the time, it was very much in the offing. There were problems about, for example, which we both wrote about together, of disability income, of recognising that if you sought compensation through the courts, that was a very hi
t and miss exercise. It was rather like spinning a roulette wheel. And just to illustrate it, which I often use this example, but it\rquote 
s worth repeating. There was another Walker, a student at the University, who was a fine footballer, and one day, he was ret
urning, or going to Devon on a motorbike, and a lorry in front of him turned right just as he was overtaking it. He broke his back. He\rquote 
s been disabled from the waist downwards ever since. I went with him, as his Supervisor, to the Inns of Court, to argue t
he interesting question of compensation, you have to kind of review what the expected earnings are of a person, in law. And, of course, I built up the strongest case possible about this fine student, who was bound to get an Upper Second, and would, theref
o
re, be bound to go into the Civil Service, that he wanted to do, and that he was bound to be promoted in that, and we ended up with a fine salary at the end, and compensation of five figures or more, five, six figures. And I remember that there was a paus
e in the proceedings at lunch time, when the insurance company offered him \'a320,000, it was then quite a considerable sum, I may say, we\rquote 
re talking about the early seventies now, but offered a very considerable sum to settle out of court. And in the meantime, by the early afternoon, one crucial witness changed his story, and he got nothing. He wasn\rquote t awarded a bean. And he\rquote 
s been on Supplementary Benefit and National Assistance ever since. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 I haven\rquote t forgotten that story. And it\rquote 
s very pertinent to the whole question of whether you ... Yes, there may be some things where compensation at law is appropriate, but disability isn\rquote t one of them. And we were both incensed about that kind of experience. I can\rquote 
t remember now, to be absolutely honest with you, whether 
that had happened or was happening around that time. However, we both wrote about the virtues of a public compensation scheme that was based on degree of disability, and that, ideally, that ought to be operated through National Insurance, and therefore th
at our provisions for disabled people, under National Insurance, ought to be extended. And this was becoming a very live and important issue in the early seventies, just as pensions and poverty and families had become big in the earlier years. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 And the Gov
ernment issued some derisory report. We called a meeting in the House of Commons, at which there were a number of other people representing disability organisations, who expressed their horror. And it was in the aftermath of that that Alan and I coming to
gether and talking it over in the corridors of the Department of Sociology at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Essex{\*\xmlclose}, said, \'93Well, why don\rquote t we start a campaigning body on a universal or comprehensive disability income?\'94
 Meaning that although this, naturally, would be underwritten by 
some general contributions, that if everybody stood a risk of either getting mildly or severely disabled, that there ought to be a national income for disabled people, varied according to the severity of their disability, whether they were at work or not,
 because if they were able to work well and good, but the disability itself should allow them an income they could count on. So we devised all this. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
And I remember from, it was really from - it was developed by me, sitting in a cottage in Higham, just at 
a time when I was - my first wife Ruth and I were divorcing, and I was leading a rather lonely, excluded life at Higham, working at the University, but having a lot of time in the evenings; and this is when I literally, I must have literally, committed at
 
least 20 hours a week to the foundation of the Disability Alliance. And we developed a Disability Rights Handbook, Alan and I, which we devised and wrote, and which Brenda Corti edited for us. I mean, it was all done on a shoestring, and then published. A
nd that, in view of the Child Poverty Action Group experience, we knew was going to be a winner, eventually, in terms of providing that basic income, because lots of people want to know about their rights when they\rquote 
re disabled, their rights to various kinds of benefit \endash 
 Mobility Allowance, Disability Living Allowance etc.. And we knew that this would be a basis for a continuing group. And we had a Steering Committee, as we called it, rather than an Executive Committee, of half and half disabled and non-disab
led people. No, it was a very positive and happy period of setting up a new campaigning body, because it was so self-evidently worthwhile to do this, and it allowed us to break out of the restrictive operation of many voluntary bodies. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 All of us are awar
e that there are organisations for spastics and the mentally handicapped, for the deaf, the blind. There are hundreds, even thousands of bodies operating for different disability groups, most of which, are very small in their numbers that they represent, 
a
nd yet, quite clearly, if you try to estimate the numbers of people who are disabled in the population as a whole, you get to very large figures indeed. The nationally representative estimate of the Office of Population Censuses and Surveys was of six and
 a half million people in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Britain{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, and we knew we were speaking for a very large number, and we campaigned vociferously, and argued for this comprehensive income. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Now, the Government never attempted to examine that particular idea. It was scared to do so, because it was so obviously going to cost a lot of money. What they did do, though, which I don\rquote 
t think they would have otherwise done, was to devise a series of supplementary measures, or complementary measures, or partial measures, to
 serve the needs for income of people with disabilities. And Alf Morris was a signal figure, as Minister for the Disabled, during the period 1974-79, and a number of very useful Bills were enacted. At the time, I was pretty critical of these as partial me
asures, that they didn\rquote t go far enough, and they weren\rquote 
t kind of consistent or coherent enough, or comprehensive enough. And in a sense I was right, because disabled and non-disabled people, there is an inequality which is morally and socially unjustifiable. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
But in the light of what has happened, or rather, not happened since 1979, it\rquote s quite evident that, really, this was the high point of work for the disabled, during this period \rquote 74-\rquote 79. A lot of people don\rquote 
t even know that, or give credit to it. But th
ere were a number of very good measures which helped disabled people to have that bit more income and that bit more acknowledgement of the situation they were in, and it gave more of them greater self-confidence to be able to speak about it, and to be abl
e to contribute to political activity in that way. I still think the Disability Alliance is - politicians feel that, \'93Oh well, it\rquote s a worthy cause, but it\rquote s not really politics\'94
. There are a lot of issues that are discussed like that, and issues which really affect very small minorities, especially if they affect well-off people they\rquote 
re given a lot more publicity than things which affect millions of people, and which are really extraordinarily important to prioritise in relation to number. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 S
o the Disability Alliance soldiered on, and has soldiered on since the 1970s. It\rquote s gone up and down hill. It\rquote s had - like many of these campaigning bodies, it\rquote 
s had its staff problems at times, of the staff getting a bit too too conscious of equality among
 themselves, rather than an inequality between disabled and non-disabled people. And one got into the ludicrous situation of people who were working their socks off 16 hours a day, seven days a week, as the primary policy investigators and campaigners hav
ing to accept the same salary, or near enough the same salary, as somebody who was secretary coming in at ten in the morning and going at five in the afternoon. And it\rquote s very difficult to shake off that kind of inverse status feeling.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Where did that ideology of equal payment come from?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Well, it arose from people who seemed to get involved in politics more for obtaining control within the organisation within which they operate: you find it within Local Authorities to a certain extent too. Yes, 
you find it in private companies, but there it\rquote 
s exercised by the management. But it appears that when, quite rightly, the lower ranks have more say, [and] it is important that they do have more say, the problem then is that there has to be some measure of, as it were, not that the word \'93incentive
\'94 is overdone, you need more than incentive: you have to have recognition of the unsocial hours that are worked, you have to have some recognition of the stress that is borne, you have to have some measures to diff
erentiate in an organisation which has little enough money anyway, that\rquote s what I\rquote m trying to say. You would have to work out these problems if all private companies were nationalised or taken into public ownership, you\rquote 
d still have the problems of sorting out fair incomes, and you just can\rquote t - although I always used to believe in equal incomes for everybody, you have to have some kind of variation, even if it\rquote 
s modest, between those who are, for one reason or another - either the structure of the organisation, or what can be offered, the cause which you\rquote re fighting for - who are carrying more than their fair share of it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 You didn\rquote t run CPAG like that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 It was very egalitarian, equal pay. Equal pay, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 But there wasn\rquote t the same problem?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Yes, there was. All the organisations which have sought to - of course, the problem there with them is both external and internal. There\rquote s an internal pro
blem in the sense that, naturally, jealousies grow, and feelings of injustice grow. I mean, seriously, if one\rquote 
s just pottering around answering [letters], sticking stamps on the post and so on, and you also have an ability to [contribute to] the job definition and maintain a very low profile - let\rquote 
s say, there was a serious political problem, internally, of getting agreement to understand and recognise the undue pressure that some people are placed under in that system. But externally, you had the problem that many organisations have - it\rquote 
s rather like millenarianism, the well-known sociological phenomenon of groups that are set up on islands in the distant Pacific, to run the ideal society, or at Stonehenge, or wherever - you know, however well they\rquote re prep
ared to behave to each other, they\rquote ve still got an outside society to cope with and to communicate with. And if outside society thinks the opposite, you\rquote 
ve got a very hard time in adjusting between the two. And this is also true of those organisations like - I mean, Child Poverty Action Group isn\rquote 
t the only one - which are striving to both recognise unequal work and the desirability of equal pay. And under any system, you obviously have problems. But it\rquote s ironic that some extremely Left-wing groups are more preoccupied with, let\rquote 
s say, their own salvation than salvation of the cause in which they\rquote re working.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 And your role as Chairman would partly involve?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Struggling to kind of equate the two, yes. It happened all through the time at Child Pove
rty Action - not much in the early years. Again, I think it\rquote s important to say that when you start organisations, when they are begun, rather like I was describing in relation to the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname PlaceType}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}University{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname PlaceName}}Essex{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, there are opportunities and excitements and enthusiasms in which everybody shares at the beginning. There\rquote 
s no problem. But when they get settled down, and when you get, you know, people finding a little niche which is very comfortable and not demanding, and who are then entitled to stay till they\rquote 
re 60 or 65, you begin to get problems. And all organisations that age have problems as much as individuals have problems when they age.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 And your role as Chairman was very similar in the two, would you say? Or was it different with Dis
ability Alliance?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 It\rquote 
s a group which is much more difficult to secure smooth operation, for a variety of reasons. One is that, of course, if possible, you should welcome somebody who\rquote s severely disabled in some respect, in order to work. And theref
ore it has to be harder to work out the construction of the job, and the rota to go with it. It\rquote 
s also more difficult in the sense that there are different disabilities represented, and people who are, as it were, immersed and their every breath is lived a
nd breathed within a particular environment; and many people who have - I mean the deaf, people who are deaf, hard of hearing, people who are blind, they have their own culture in a way, which is extraordinarily fascinating to learn about, but not easy to
 [absorb into an effective organisation]. And they\rquote re not familiar, often, in, let\rquote 
s say, organisations with the sighted, or with people who have learning difficulties, to take an even more extreme and difficult instance, or schizophrenics. And quite apart 
from the sharing of the gender role that we strive for, and the generational gap that can grow, to manage to get into acceptable association, a group of executive members representing disabled organisations, is not as straightforward, can\rquote 
t be as straightforward as a steering committee representing activists in child poverty from Lancashire and Newcastle, and Scotland and London. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 It seems to me there are more difficulties. And it\rquote 
s almost like - it puts a bit of a strain on their operation, because people
 have to be sensitive to them, and that often can imply that certain subjective matters are not publicly stated, and there has to be more quiet negotiation behind the scenes to make them run effectively and with comprehension and understanding. There must
 be, there are a lot of other points about the differences between the two. I think it\rquote s fair to say that some people work with disability groups because of - well, the problem used to be, of running a charitable activity, was that you\rquote 
d get people who were retired admirals or field-marshals, who didn\rquote 
t have a clue about disability, who were wheeled into positions of power, and were disasters to the organisations they were supposed to represent and manage. You might be able to run a battleship, but running t
he Spastics Society is a different order of skill! But I suppose the problem today is one more of lords and ladies. I mean, I am very much a critic of the peerage system and the way in which that tends to cloy the management and programme of activities of
 
organisations concerned with disabled people, you know, it counts for a lot, and yet what one wants are people voted into the position by virtue of a membership which is active and involved. And that is as necessary to some of our major charitable and cam
paigning organisations as it is to the House of Lords.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 So you have an active involved membership with Disability Alliance?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Yes. It has a kind of trickle-down representation. By that I mean that there are, oh, 250 organisational members of it,
 most of which receive one, two or more copies of the Disability Rights Handbook each year, which is the staple diet and reason for them being connected. But they also, both nominally and in fact, have a say not only in the recruitment of a Steering Commi
ttee, but in the programme of activities, and campaigning activities of the Group. It\rquote 
s not easy to breathe truthful, democratic values into a very unwieldy set of organisations, some of which vary enormously in the number of members as well as the commitment and involvement of the membership. But it\rquote 
s very fascinating to try to keep track of it, and why I think it\rquote s all-important is that it helps some groups who would otherwise be very isolated, into a belief that they do share certain of their problems, if
 not all of them, with a lot of others, and enables them to have access to others for information and consolation in all sorts of respects. So I\rquote m a great believer in federalism, in that respect.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 And in terms of personalities, who have been the important figures in the Disability Alliance?
