\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 He\rquote 
s I think, more diplomatic than I am, and obtains respect and confidence steadily, and without reversal. He\rquote s very patient. Sometimes he\rquote s a bit long-winded! He\rquote d laugh if he heard me saying this! But indefatigable in som
e ways, which I regard as quite remarkable in someone who has those difficulties. It\rquote 
s so easy for people with a disability of the major kind to, perhaps, contribute with great energy for a few years, but to actually be able to go on with it, despite all t
he disappointments, and despite all the discouragements, and the indifference that too many people display, I think that is quite extraordinary. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
I mean, there are extraordinary figures in British politics now, who are disabled. I mean, the two who stand out in my mind are David Blunkett, who is quite miraculous in his ability, and not just his receptivity. I mean, it\rquote 
s quite true that the officials at the Department of Education say he is the most energetic of all the Ministers of Education they\rquote ve known 
since the War, or Secretaries of State for Education. And they thought they were in for a quiet time when they heard of his appointment, but they\rquote ve discovered otherwise since! But he\rquote 
s remarkable in his perception and his receptivity and his command of ev
erything, despite his disability. Another person rather like that, who was profoundly deaf until new technology transformed his life, was Jack Ashley who, I think, contributed to the cause immensely over the years, and who I had a lot to do with when he w
as first at Cambridge, because we were there together, long ago. 
