re expected to attend, and that everybody expects them to attend, and so on, to begin to comprehend that they have to work with more than that one representative Member of Parliament, they have to work with a number of different groups. It\rquote 
s taught me that the teamwork, the collaborative work, is as important to those pushing Members of Parliament as it is to the Members of Parliament themselves. They need collaboration above all. I think that, particularly at the
 present time, giving welfare reform as an example, I learnt over welfare reform that the number of Members of Parliament who were unhappy about lone parents, and the rights of people in the disabled population, which blew up just before Christmas 1997, t
his was much more widely shared. This is one of the things I\rquote ve learned as a near insider in Parliament. And that one of the problems, our problems with Parliamentarians is that they\rquote 
re treated, really, too much as cannon fodder as individuals, and don\rquote t appreciate enough themselves, that if they want some of their values and their principles to be observed, they\rquote 
ve got to work more frequently together, and, okay, some of that has to be by spontaneous combustion from time to time. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
