\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Yes, why not! (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par 
\par [Further comment, 24 February 1999]
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Being an MP's spouse also means seeing a fair amount of the leading political players; being in Parliament at times of high drama - like the cliff hanger v
otes on Europe when John Major was Prime Minister; having invaluable access to the House of Commons Library, its research staff, and staff in charge of publications and room bookings. In the past the spouse has generally been a wife, very distant, and not
 
much there. The growth in the number of women MPs has in practice given unexpected opportunities of observation and minor participation to men. When a spouse is a paid research assistant - like Leo Beckett, who does a fine job - this can be a major involv
ement. I have backed up Jean with data for speeches, the pursuit of key contemporary matters on health, the accountability of statisticians, and the art of developing a series of Parliamentary questions. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Since from May 1997 she has needed at least one mem
ber of paid staff in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}Westminster{\*\xmlclose} rather than all in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, I have spent more time at LSE and less in the House of Commons. Nevertheless, in 1999, for example, I have had long exchanges with Michael Meacher, Tony Benn, David Blunkett, Alan Si
mpson, Betty Boothroyd, Dennis Skinner, Malcolm Wicks, Ann Keen, John Prescott, Margaret Beckett and others in chance meetings and over meals. I've also had the opportunity even in these few weeks of attending All-Party Parliamentary Groups on Disability 
a
nd on Children, and the Treasury and Social Security Select Committees. Thus I gave written evidence on the day of writing this (24 February) to the Social Security Committee on Child Benefit, and spoke yesterday at the Campaign in Defence of the Welfare 
State on the new Bill on Pensions and Welfare. However, my input is tiny in quantity and quality to that of Jean, my wife, who is without doubt one of the dozen most creative and well-organised talents on Labour's benches!]
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par Part Eight: Interview held on 1st February, 1999
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 We\rquote 
re going to talk about your personal life, and we have already gone through your childhood, and meeting Ruth, and getting married. And I think we mentioned the birth Matthew and Adam, which was 1952 and 1953?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Yes, that\rquote s right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 And so you had two other boys with her, Christian and Ben?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
I did, indeed. Ruth had one or two miscarriages. This is one reason which affects so many families, so many women, to have to bear that agony, 
which meant that there was a delay between each of the second and third, and third and fourth. And, of course, like so many couples, I suppose we sought to have another child in the belief that we might likely have a daughter. And Christian was born, he w
a
s actually called Paul Christian, but both he and ourselves tended to prefer the very unusual name, as it was then, Christian. He was born in 1957. And Ben, Benjamin, was born in 1962. So a gap of four or five years between the second and third, and third
 and fourth. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Did you always want to have quite a big family?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Originally - I think couples in those days, even professional couples, tended to be rather romantic. The intention was to benefit from large families, and Ruth and I shared an aspi
ration of having six children, originally, and began to modify that somewhat, because one or two of those births were quite difficult, and I think that this affected us, as did our ... you know, as we got older, we changed a little in our attitudes to wha
t we wanted to get out of life, and whether we had already developed a substantial enough family.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Can you talk a little about being a father at that time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Looking back now, I have very mixed feelings about whether I did enough. And, on the whole, I think that I didn
\rquote t do enough by 1990s standards. I think this is common to many men, older men. I did do a number of things. I kind of embraced fatherhood, I never forget the day that my first-born, Matthew, arrived. I happened to be present, excep
t for a few minutes, and I remember, literally, dancing in the streets that morning, back in February 1952.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Was that a home birth?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 That was a home birth. In fact, three of our four children, by Ruth, were born at home, and the second, Adam, 
was born at the local Maternity Home, in the top of Heath Street, only because we\rquote 
d just moved house, and were still trying to get the place straight for the family, and because of all this, Ruth was booked in to the Maternity Home for that birth, and neit
her of us thought very much of the way in which they kept fathers away. And I have never forgotten it, as the kind of disparaging treatment that men received at that time. And, of course, all of that changed, even during the period until we had our third 
and fourth, it was beginning to change quite rapidly. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
We were romantically egalitarian, but accepted a kind of division of labour, and talked about complementarity. I mean, many men still, today, excuse themselves from taking on some of the chores of domestic life on grounds that, well, even if they didn
\rquote t do the cooking or the washing-up, or the washing, that they did other things which showed that they did play some part in domestic life. The obvious one is do-it-yourself work within the home, and some m
en do the gardening, grow vegetables, or clean the windows and so on. I mean, there are divisions of labour which are excused. I don\rquote t mean that you can\rquote 
t be complementary, you have to be, in terms of your division of labour, but in many cases, men, at that time, excused it. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
I took young Matthew out in a push-chair when, for just a year, we lived in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Westminster{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 after he was first born. We moved to Hampstead in a very working-class cul-de-sac, as it was in those days. It no longer is, of course! B
ut it was, at that time, a cul-de-sac with a warehouseman, a carpenter and a fish and chip restaurateur, and there was a local builder [as well as widowed pensioners living alone]. But, on the whole, they were working-class men and women in this small cul
-
de-sac of houses where we lived. And I tended to take both Matthew and then Adam, when they were young, out, in the early morning, with the dog. We had an Alsatian dog, and went to Hampstead Heath regularly, before I went to work. That was a common practi
ce. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 I regret that I didn\rquote 
t come home frequently enough at, say, six o\rquote clock, to get them to bed, and to read to them. [While interviewing in Bethnal Green, and then touring {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname country-region}}England{\*\xmlclose} and 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Wales{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} to compile }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 The Last Refuge}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
, I was often home after 7 p.m.] But I did do quite a bit of that at weekends, and sporadically ... I used to have the practice of composing, in my head, and telling stories. And I thoroughly enjoyed that. I loved it, in fact. And I remember doing that wi
th all of my four sons. Probably I didn\rquote t do it frequently enough, and certainly I didn\rquote 
t do enough of the kind of sitting with sons when they were coping with ... not just homework, but reactions to school, and reading, etc.. I tended to too much take the 
attitude that school-work was for the teachers to impart, and if I tried to add to it, I was giving them a more privileged introduction to life. This was a crazy thing to believe, but you have to consider that, at that time, certainly after the War, and u
p
 to the early fifties, living your Socialism was really an idea which seems to me now, to have been stronger then, that more people actually believed they should behave as egalitarians, even if they had the money not to be. I mean, there are some distingu
ished examples of that, of Labour Cabinet Ministers, the Labour Leader, before the War, had lived very simply. Herbert Morrison [also] lived, by today\rquote s standards, extraordinarily simply.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Was it George Lansbury you meant?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 George Lansbury was 
the man I had in mind, and I have a great admiration for him. He tended to be derided more than he deserved, but was an extraordinary example, nationally as well as locally, and certainly locally, he was affectionately regarded as someone who helped to ho
ld the community together [ - as Bob Holman's fine biography shows]. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
And I took this seriously in my youth. I came to it intellectually, and by chance during the War. It\rquote s a mixture of two things. There was no particular reason why, I mean, [that the influence came] through family, because I hadn\rquote 
t got a father around. I came to Socialism during the War, and people were so full of aspirations then, for changing the face of the world, and I shared in that, and I was young and idealistic. So it was partly in
tellectual, in that sense. It was partly a shared experience too, as I\rquote 
ve said before, of Air Raid Precaution, service in the Army, where you encountered people of very different class, and I gained from that mixing, and I think a lot of other people gaine
d too. And, as it were, it entered into the way in which one approached life. I think it helped to maintain a greater real equality of earnings between people at a time of full employment, which also, of course, helped to maintain the narrowing of the gap
 between rich and poor during that period. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
And I felt this, but took it, probably, to somewhat extreme lengths, in terms of not wanting to confer on my children privileges because of my position and my occupation. And I regret that now, not doing more in 
terms of their home education, though I think some of it they picked up indirectly. Then, in the late fifties, I was getting too multiply involved in both teaching and research, and tended to come home seven o\rquote 
clockish, so from even the days when I was wor
king in the centre of London, quite apart from those days when I was interviewing in far-flung corners of England, there were gaps in my continuing fatherhood. So I look back with some regret on not being around more than I was.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 And what about weekends, what was the pattern then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Weekends were quite a pleasure. We were quite sociable. We had a lot to do with our neighbours. Living in a cul-de-sac was a small community, and successively, there were girls from the neighbourhood, I can remember 
two, three of them, who each, for a few years, had a lot to do with coming in and out, and, in fact, taking some care of the boys. To what extent this was their natural disposition, I think it was, it was a concern. Being a little mother, in other words, 
was again, a very strong working-class feature, and if you didn\rquote 
t have your own brothers and sisters to care for, it was quite a common thing to do it for others. We shared in that to a fair extent, and enjoyed having contact with neighbours, some of whom c
ame in and out, and I remember keenly, Ruth looking after one lovely woman living locally, who, for quite some weeks and months, in her terminal illness. So there was quite a full neighbourly existence during this period. Weekends, visiting family, playin
g
 sport, we certainly were fortunate, both locally, and going on to the Heath, for walks. Our holidays during this period, came to be frequently going to seaside. I remember, particularly, going to Aldeburgh for a few years in succession, during those year
s when my sons were growing up. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
And Ruth and I, occasionally, were fortunate enough to be able to get the sons looked after by her mother, in particular, and the coming and goings of our respective mothers was quite intensive. Less so my mother, for reaso
ns which I think are quite interesting, but common, that it tends to be the maternal grandmother who plays a part with children, and this was something I learned, had already learned and found quite acceptable and ordinary! And so, yes, we developed frien
d
ships outside, mainly through work, I suppose. Partly, also, through family. Ruth had quite a large extended kin network, and there were occasions when we visited them, say, for a Saturday wedding, I can remember, one or two occasions of that kind. Fiftie
s was a time of, as it were, developing these different activities in life, and being able to conduct some of them almost to conditions of, well, I was going to say excellence, but to the fullest extent that was possible in one\rquote s adult life. 

\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 We were at the height of physical powers, let\rquote 
s say, in our twenties and early thirties, and both enjoyed physical activity as well as a lot of intellectual activity, family activity. And I suppose we both shared an aspiration, too, which people come back to, of wantin
g to get a balance in their lives. All of us have the aim of being able to have a very satisfying and fulfilled home life, domestic life, and many people are lucky enough to be able to share that in their occupations. They\rquote 
re very content with outside work, earned occupations, they don\rquote 
t usually have much control over the hours. The predictability and routine and pattern of life is less easy to follow now than it was then, having set hours, like not having shops open at weekends, helped, really, to have thi
s more settled and predictable and regularised life, and we were very much involved in that, so that we tried to say to ourselves, \'93Well, we had to have a good family life, we had to have a good-looking home\'94, activities \endash 
 painting, carpentry, etc., was very important. We had to cook, cook ourselves.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 This is at home, you mean?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 You were painting, or the children, you\rquote re talking about?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 I was meaning decorating.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Oh, you did decorating?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 A lot in those early days. In fact, I did most of that sort of thing in our first home in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}Mansfield Place{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} in Hampstead.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 And carpentry you did as well?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Bits and pieces, yes. There have been a lot of laughs about my not altogether
 successful skills in [carpentry. I laid rubber tiles and put in a fixed table in the kitchen made of formica stuck to a flush door, perched on legs made of piping].
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 So you did some do-it-yourself. Did you do any cooking and cleaning, and things like that, or not?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
I did very little cleaning. I quite often cleaned the windows, as one of my roles. I often cooked a Sunday meal. I remember cooking a chicken, or a pork jo
int. I certainly did that. But that was dwarfed, really, by both the cooking that Ruth undertook, and her mother. Her mother contributed quite a lot to the meals that we had as a young family. And I suppose taking children out, Ruth was much more the one 
who collected children from school and got them cleaned up and into bed. I was the one who quite often took my sons to school in the morning, before I was going to work. I\rquote 
m saying this, as you can gather, somewhat hesitantly, because it did fluctuate from 
period to period, depending where I was and what I was up to, in terms of the work enterprise. So it was a full and very affectionate family life, and there are riotous memories that I have of the children and their behaviour, and their activities. Of cou
rse, they were absolutely full of energy and tearing up and down the local alleys. Being a cul-de-sac, we didn\rquote 
t really have a road within the nearest 100 yards, so there was a lot of playing in the so-called alley, and the path in front of the group of cottages in this cul-de-sac, and I, increasingly, took an interest in the athletics of my children. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
One of my great, loveliest memories, is trying to encourage first Matthew, and then Matthew and Adam, in going down to Parliament Hill Fields, to the running
 track, and encouraging them to practice sports. And I suppose I was someone who took an active interest in them playing football and cricket and so on. I loved those sports myself, and had been reasonably successful at them. I wanted my son, Matthew, to 
b
e - and I thought he could be - a considerable athlete and runner, and took him to Parliament Hill Fields. I think he tired of that possibility more than lacked the skill to bring it to success. But I remember giving a broadcast on one occasion, in which 
I spoke of the real aesthetic pleasure of athletics, which I\rquote d enjoyed earlier, and which I sought to pass on to him. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Unless I convey the kind of interruptions to routine family life [which we experienced], it\rquote s difficult for others to quite comprehend that. I mean, one of the interruptions ... I\rquote 
ve just mentioned giving a broadcast. The fact of the matter is that I did, because of the kind of things I was doing, in terms of research and academia, and outside interests in politics and voluntary bodies, the
re were quite a lot of interruptions for radio and television performances. It wasn\rquote t that frequent, but quite often an interruption for a Saturday or a Sunday, or an evening, would mean that I was doing things of that kind.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Which sports were you still active in at this point?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Running. I can remember doing this right up to the time when my sons reached the end of their teens. When we went not only to Aldeburgh, but when we went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Somerset{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, to Marghanita Laski\rquote s house she owned in th
e country [at Buckland St Mary. This was several summers. The garden] was always overgrown when we arrived, and we cleared up all the debris around the house, and cut back the overgrown bushes, this was a period when I remember, each day, having a two or 
three mile run to keep myself fit. I was still pretending to myself that I was a good cross-country athlete. And I went on with that, oh, for certainly that period, and fitfully thereafter into my forties. So it wasn\rquote 
t really until towards the end of my for
ties that I dropped fairly regular cross-country running in whatever surroundings I could find. I still enjoyed that. I gave up rugby in my mid-twenties. I still played cricket at 60, locally here, at Tortworth in Gloucestershire. When we first came here 
i
n 1987, I played a little cricket for the village, not much, a few games, until I went out one brilliant summer day, forgot that I was no longer 25 or 30, and bounced around trying to bowl, trying to bat, and the tendons of my feet got damaged, and I was 
hobbling around for weeks afterwards! And I decided, well, maybe I was taking a good thing too far! (LAUGHS)
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
But going back to the fifties, you mention relationships with neighbours and family. Did you have friends to the house, and cook for them, very often, or not?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Fairly often, yes. It was a mixture of - Ruth\rquote 
s mother joining us, for example, of local friends coming. Being Hampstead, there were quite a lot of professional friends. There were journalists we knew, who we were very fond of. Th
ere was a doctor we were very fond of. There were a few politicians from further afield, and, I suppose, in those days -this was both in the late fifties and into the sixties, right through the sixties - there were people who we were quite close to - Caro
l
 and Tony Benn, Dick and Ann Crossman, Peter and Liz Shore - there were others, but these were, literally, friends made in the expansionist era of Labour politics in the late fifties and early and mid-sixties. It was during that period that we had a very 
active, almost public life, in some respects - I've explained this earlier, about the work on National Superannuation and so on, and that\rquote 
s the tie-up. But, personally, those friendships meant a considerable amount to us. And Brian Abel-Smith was also a key
 figure in those exchanges at that time, and was a very close friend. Friendships were formed both at the London School of Economics, where I was for a long time, and then when I went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Colchester{\*\xmlclose}
, I think that ... if you\rquote re asking me ...
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 I\rquote m trying to focus on the fifties, before you went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Essex
{\*\xmlclose}.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Ah! Well, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, in the late fifties, these were some of the people we knew very well. The {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Dickinsons{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 is one family I can remember. He was a doctor. And they lived
 a few hundred yards away. There was a fair amount of coming and going, certainly by Ruth, to families like them. And evening-wise, so far as the men were concerned too, of both going to have a meal with them, and them coming to us in the evening too.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Was that a very formal kind of meal? A dinner party?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Yes, it was semi-formal. I mean, it was an occasion everybody could enjoy. It was a special occasion, so sometimes you\rquote d put candles on the table, and you\rquote d have nice starched table-cloths and napkins and so on, and a bottle of wine \endash 
 what everyone experiences today, I hope, a lot of people do, when they entertain those they care about. And we had a nice network of people we cared about \endash  Norman and Jean McK
enzie. Norman McKenzie is - his wife, unhappily, is dead from cancer, but Norman McKenzie, I only met him in the LSE the other day by chance. I haven\rquote 
t seen him for 20 years! This is an event older people experience with great pleasure, that they come across people that they\rquote 
ve known well as friends earlier in life, and usually for accidental reasons, they have not seen much of each other for 20 years or more.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 And were there things that you and Ruth did on your own together, just to enjoy yourselves?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Yes. There were special occasions when we went to what then became the Festival Hall, of course, I can remember; of evening dinners out; occasions when we had a treat of that kind. I think it was less frequent when children are young. I mean, this
 is a common experience of couples with young children, that they resort to formalities, when they can get baby-sitters, when they can get a grandparent to look after the children for an evening, and it\rquote 
s a special effort in going out that way. I suppose we had, I\rquote m trying to remember hard, we didn\rquote 
t do it often, but we tried to do it sometimes. It was like going to the opera, or the ballet, or ... dancing, very rarely, I suppose, after our young adult life. Yes, we enjoyed dancing, but usually only when it arose by chance at somebody else\rquote 
s party. That was lovely.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 But you went to the Festival Hall for music?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Yes. I think both of us were very fond of doing that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Is there anything more about that period, the fifties, that you think we should know?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
We talked of the humdrum realities of everyday existence. I suppose, being aroused politically, is a memory that crops up repeatedly, of course, that affects one\rquote s life, and even what we do. And I mean by that, living in an area where it
 was literally true that there were people of, well, wealth as well as professional class, but also manual labourers, and newly-arrived immigrants from the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Caribbean{\*\xmlclose}
. This we luxuriated in, in a way. We knew we were lucky that we had around us, within very short distances, people of every class and age. Now, this is getting less common today. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 We were seized by it, but also endeavoured to respond. We didn
\rquote t want to regard this as sort of artificial. It wasn\rquote t passing your neighbour by. There were a nu
mber of neighbours in each class who we got to know extraordinarily well, and as a consequence, were aroused by political ill-treatment. I mean, this arose with a newspaper man who was badly treated by the Social Services. It arose from the terminal illne
ss of another, which I\rquote 
ve already alluded to. It arose through the treatment of Irish immigrants, because the woman who worked with us, helped us with the huge amount of washing for such a large family, was Irish, and brought us into touch with a lot of the
 events that were happening to the Irish in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname PlaceName}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Camden{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. So there was a sense in which our ordinary domestic and neighbourhood life fuelled our interest in politics, but also was fuelled by politics itself, with events outside which 
impinged on their lives. And that was a fantastic asset that we realised was not that common, and quite important.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Did you want to give a sketch of one of those people, and what happened to them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 It would certainly be possible to do so. I think I\rquote 
ve already sketched one or two. [One] of the most extraordinary events [was] of the newspaper seller with a club foot, and was recovering from pneumonia, or trying to recover from pneumonia ... I\rquote ve specified this, haven\rquote t I? If I haven
\rquote t, then this 
was an ... He sold newspapers by Hampstead tube. He had a club foot. He did it for many years. He got very little income. He lived with his mother in a flat in New End, New End flats, which, to this day, are pretty run of the mill, very poor Council flats
, [less than] a hundred yards from where we lived, literally. And I can\rquote 
t remember how we found this out, but we learned that his mother was dying in one room, and he was ill with pneumonia in another. And it was deep winter, the sewage system had broken, t
he pipes were burst, and sewage had leaked down on to their floor, and had frozen solid, an inch thick, or whatever. And we went into this situation, we were at work, tried to do what we could to help, immediately. Contacted the Social Services. Apparentl
y
, they, in their wisdom, sent round, partly because of the elderly mother, sent round some volunteers who were supposed to be caring for the elderly, and they left half a bottle of disinfectant on the mantle-piece, as their contribution to [the couple's] 
welfare, and departed. And we discovered this the day after, or so on. And it was this kind of ill-organised and poor sense of priorities which stirred us immensely. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
A man locally, only again a hundred yards, 150 yards away, an old man, I think he was the
n 75ish, 78ish, that kind of age, who lived in appalling circumstances, who we visited repeatedly, got his shopping, and to our dismay, was found dead with his ginger cat on his chest. And the way in which that had happened was like touching a raw nerve. 
No doubt there are such events today, and maybe more of them, where people are ignored by neighbours, where family, they\rquote 
ve become disconnected for one reason or another. It seems to happen more to men than women. Women become isolated, yes, because the men
 die first, but the men are the ones who get disconnected more easily, who have been responsible for separation from wives, and deserting children, but then get beached like flotsam and jetsam, and seem to withdraw into themselves in pensionable age, and 
don\rquote t have much contact. I\rquote m giving him as an example. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 I\rquote 
ve mentioned the elderly, but, of course, there were younger families who we cared about, who had their problems. There was the man, again, a hundred yards away in New End flats, where neighbours spoke to us about him, the man, being a ne\rquote 
er-do-good. He was unemployed. They felt that he could get work, and that he was sponging on the State. And we discovered that he hadn\rquote t just given up his job as a lorry driver, to sponge on the State and get Unempl
oyment Benefit, but that his doctor had discovered that he had a terminal heart condition. And the neighbours were quietened at the discovery, only six or eight weeks later, when he died at the age of 32. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 So when these events happen in your local communi
ty, they leave a mark that can\rquote t be erased. And to some extent, that personal experience, [in] that home existence the interchange with politics and professional life is enormous. It explains why it\rquote 
s so valuable, I think it helps you correct your prioriti
es in discovering what is precious and important. And, you know, there were a lot of other experiences of that kind, which we valued, both good and bad. One of the happy, most happy occasions I remember, was that we were in a very small cottage, you have 
to remember here that the rooms were, oh, I\rquote 
d be surprised if it was more than 14 feet by 12, the biggest room, but we divided this room, the front room, in this kind of burgeoning energetic phase of our early adult and family life, we decided to have a pan
tomime for the neighbours. And I erected a curtain across the middle of the room, and we got a dozen people packed in, in one half, behind the curtain. We managed to get about 12 neighbours into this half of the room, sitting on little wooden chairs. And 
in the other half, we had a performance, which my sons, and especially these little mothers we\rquote re talking about, were giving performances in turn - I can\rquote 
t remember now the exact sequence, exact programme, but song and dance routines. And the neighbours ado
red this. They thought this was a great occasion. We did this a few times, and that, too, is enormously rewarding. It lays a basis for local involvement, but also family building, building [between] generations. Now, I\rquote 
m talking, as you can see, not so much saying my personal life or family life was one thing, politics and occupational life was another; [but that] these were inextricably mixed, and fed each other.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 It\rquote s almost like you were living out the ideal of the extended family and involvement w
ith neighbours that you also saw in Bethnal Green.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 I think that was partly conscious. Some of it was unconscious, some of it was na\'efve. But I don\rquote 
t want to give an impression of smug self-satisfaction about it, that didn\rquote t apply. Just to give one example, I look back now, and at the time, I was incapable, really, of helping my mother enough at [that] time. I\rquote 
ve explained already that she was quite well-known on the stage. And then in her forties, suddenly nobody wanted to know her, because she\rquote 
d lost her looks, and she withdrew into herself. She had the courage and strength later, in the fifties, to re-start her life as a clerk in an oil company office, but I can remember days and ...
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 I remember going to see her, a mile away, in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}Belsize Crescent{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 in Hampstead, and being completely disconcerted. Because sometimes I would find her with a half-eaten Sunday meal on the arm of the sofa, in a kind of stupor of alcoholism, she was so depressed, morbidly depressed. And I, as her son, didn\rquote 
t seem to know what to do to try and get her out of it. And I was embarrassed by it. I knew she was living with a man who was also somewhat of a drunk, and who had fallen, he was like a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Brideshead Revisited}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858  man, who\rquote d fallen from grace,
 and they had high points of going to the races together, or to Lords [Cricket Ground], and he just used every bit of money that came his way, and used a lot of hers. And I suppose she found consolation in him, but it was no life at all for much of the ti
me. And she tried not to impose upon this young family a mile away \endash  ourselves. She was squeezed out, in part, by the other mother, the grandmother. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
I suppose I was dimly conscious of some of this, but I now blame myself for not responding better, with a 
bit more understanding, and involving her in different ways so that she could have more chance of surmounting this episode in her life. And I think, in saying that, there are many people, all of us have those experiences of regret that because we\rquote 
re so immersed in certain large parts of our life \endash  in our children, our immediate surroundings, the work we are doing \endash  we can\rquote t spare time, and it isn\rquote t that we don\rquote 
t spare time to attend to some of the priorities that engages both within our families in neighbou
rhoods too, so you can understand how people develop blinkers, metaphorically, if not in actual fact, so that they adopt methods of passing their neighbours by with a cheery \'93Good Morning\'94
. And we all have to do that, as well as tend to do that, and it\rquote s very difficult to try and allow it not to become both imprisoning as well as self-stultifying, I suppose. I\rquote 
ve given an example of something I feel keenly about in my own family and personal life, and on both sides, one can, as it were, take pleasure and regard as a great achievement to be able to have enjoyed certain things, and tried to do the best for one
\rquote s children, or one\rquote s nearest and dearest. Yet some of them do get squeezed out, or fall by the wayside, or get ignored, or get blamed for things which subsequent experience suggests they shouldn\rquote t be blamed for.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 So shall we move on now to when you go to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Essex{\*\xmlclose}?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
I think that goes on very smoothly. Partly at your urging, I was dwelling a bit more on those fifties when the children were young, than later on. One little thought here, in relation to the rather depressing example I\rquote 
ve just given, one of my lingering memories is of taking the boys on camping holiday, which we did several times during this period that I\rquote m talking about, the fift
ies. And I tried, stupidly, tried to combine it with going to the International Sociological Association Conference in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}Geneva{\*\xmlclose}, or near {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Geneva{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And I\rquote ll never forget Christian, at the age of two and a half, or thereabouts, dancing madly when th
e Conference had one of its evening entertainments, and we captured him on camera, with a photo. But he was one of those children who, at an early age, are regarded as just supremely attractive by everybody, and it was one of those supreme moments of exhi
l
aration, and a child symbolises that. It was exhilarating, the whole trip, but that image of him jumping in the air, with his hair flying all over - his fair hair, blue eyes -symbolises that kind of exhilaration of what family life and domestic life was m
ost treasured for. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Ruth came on that {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Geneva
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} trip?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Yes. We were living - it wasn\rquote 
t exactly a good location we chose for the tent, may I say! It got pretty depressingly wet on one or two occasions! I think most people understand the kind of disadvantages as well as the advantages of camping! (LAUGHS) But I don\rquote 
t think I really contributed much to the Conference, let\rquote s put it that way! (LAUGHS) Anyway, you asked about going to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Essex{\*\xmlclose}, and we\rquote re now going into the 1960s ?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 And how did that change your family life?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
I think it changed it dramatically, in the sense that we - we agreed, I think I was less clear about this than I should have been, and I can\rquote t remember the degree of responsibility that each of us had for this,
 but we decided to stay in London, domestically, partly because my sons, the two eldest had started at, or were soon started at comprehensive school, which were innovations, it has to be remembered. They were innovations. And in the early sixties, there w
as a tremendous enthusiasm for comprehensivisation, which spread across the political parties, and experiments in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose} were very much appreciated as well as ... supported by the 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} population. I got very much involved in that whole process, in public. And I\rquote m only saying that to emphasise why staying in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} seemed so important for the sake of the family. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 But it wasn\rquote 
t only that. We decided to experiment with commuting. I'm talking about experimenting with commuting, whereby I was going to be stuck with not merely a full-time job, but a very demanding job, starting a new university at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname 
place}}Colchester{\*\xmlclose}, 60 miles away. And we drifted into commuting on a large scale, for several years. I don\rquote t think either of us really talked serio
usly about how long that could work for, but the way we rationalised it was partly over my sons starting comprehensive school, but also because my grandmother came to stay with us. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
For roundabout the last ten years of her life until 1970, she lived at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}Mansfield Place{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. She\rquote 
d left her son, who died, who was legless from the First World War, near Portsmouth, or in Portsmouth, and she came to stay with us, and I think she was very happy, living in an upstairs small room, and she her Guinness ever
y morning! One Guinness, no more. And she loved seeing the children, they loved her. They always kept going upstairs to see her before they went to school, and after they came back from school. She was an absolute rock in the family, as she had been in my
 early life. And that ran through the sixties. So that was the other rationalisation for living in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose} and working in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Colchester{\*\xmlclose}. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
And, of course, I flouted the rule that the University developed of members of staff had to be within 25 miles. M
any universities have that kind of convention now. Those are the circumstances in which I lived for several years. The first year or two it was relatively easy. The first year, \rquote 
63, we were really just passing all the rules, planning all the courses that w
ere going to start in 1964. Come 1964, we were recruiting the first two of us on the academic staff, the first hundred students, and then expanding rapidly. So, being on the spot became necessary from October 1964. I took to driving up to Colchester, eith
er Sunday night, or at the crack of dawn on Monday morning, and driving back - I tried to make it Thursday night, partly because I was very much involved in campaigning work \endash  the Child Poverty Action Group, for example \endash 
 so that I could do something on Friday, and/or Saturday, on the spot, even sometimes by getting back early on a Thursday evening. So a practice was developed of trying to be in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}
London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} at least the three days around the weekend. And you can imagine that this became a routine, where 
I arrived back, exhausted on a Thursday evening, and was not very much of a family man, especially since I was turning my attentions to campaigning. And I remember, Ruth would get good meals ready, and I\rquote 
d arrive back on a Thursday, sit with them on my lap, and we\rquote d catch up with television, or exchanging news. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 In {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Colchester{\*\xmlclose}
, it was a miserable life. I look back on the period, not so much \rquote 63, because I\rquote m saying that that was a planning year, and I was going backwards and forwards quite a lot. But from \rquote 64 onwards, I was living, in the week, in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Colchester{\*\xmlclose} itself. At first, I partly rented a house a couple of miles from the University, towards Wivenhoe, and that was an extraordinarily miserable, damp place, that couldn\rquote 
t be heated, not properly, a
nd my memory of it is just going back late at night, filling a hot-water bottle, and dragging into bed, and then getting myself some corn flakes in the morning and getting out as fast as I could. The following year, I thought better of that little enterpr
ise, and rented a room from someone in the town, and this was partly out of self-indulgence about my political and Socialist attitudes, it was with a 97-year old man, and his daughter of 71 or thereabouts. And she was someone who was an ex-nurse, she
\rquote d work
ed at the Royal Eastern Counties mental hospital for many years. A bit of an authoritarian working-class woman, bossy nurse type. And she got me eggs and bacon in the morning, and complained about my arriving back at 11.30 at night from the University.

\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Did you eat in the evening there?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
I either went to the early evening meals provided in the University, or tried one or two cheap restaurants or cafes in the town, but I have a memory of really trying to do it on the cheap. Yes,
 of course there were exceptions when a better meal, I had a better meal sometimes with people from the University. Sometimes the Vice-Chancellor would have an evening dinner, and I went to that occasionally, but that was pretty rare. But my memory is of 
t
hese two pensioners, in a very unpretentious terraced house, and feeling I owed them a little. I realised my rent was quite important to them, and I stuck it rather longer than I would have wished, for, I think it was three or four years, up to about 1970
, as it turned out. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
All of this was not very conducive to my relationships with Ruth and sexual relations with Ruth, and I think we began to diverge. I don\rquote t think she, originally, was someone who was absorbed and engaged, with enthusiasm, with the detail
s of academic life anyway. It wouldn\rquote t be fair to expect it in some senses. But she didn\rquote t, anyway. And few people knowing this situation would think that the marriage could easily endure, given that degree of separation. I\rquote 
m surprised it endured for the time it did. But we broke up, finally, in 1974. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Before that, in 1973, Ruth had gone away for 12 months with Benjamin, who was then 11 only, with my - and I have to say this - grudging agreement. I was unhappy about it, but it was very much her idea, and a
 very courageous idea it was, but not, in the event, one which I think really did him any good, so far as his education is concerned, although it introduced him to the world in a way that few children of 11 years of age have ever been introduced. They cro
ssed the world in a Land-Rover, and had some extraordinary adventures in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname country-region}}Afghanistan{\*\xmlclose} and {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Iraq{\*\xmlclose}
{\*\xmlclose}, and places like that. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
We were so upset when she came back, about the fact that we were drifting apart, or had got apart. [And] 
I always bitterly regret this, she showed me - I kept the list of letters she wrote. She wrote long letters about these experiences, and posted them home, and I kept them as a great sheaf of letters, and put it to her that she should get it published as a
 kind of travel biography. It would have been, in my humble opinion, with editing, a good seller, a best-seller possibly. And because of the emotional spasm of the developing separation between us, she just, one day, tore this up, or, as I\rquote 
m told, burnt it.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 All the letters?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Yes. The whole lot. Why do I say that? I say it because it illustrates the traumas of a separation. Fault, people have different views about fault on either side. I think, given the circumstances, it was not surprising, to 
put it no stronger, that we both tended to look elsewhere for comfort and solace and - daily life appreciation and concern. I don\rquote t think this really was serious, and it certainly wasn\rquote 
t on my part, serious, although there were days when I was, let\rquote s say, not as committed as I had been previously, to going to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Colchester{\*\xmlclose}. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 This didn\rquote 
t become serious until the early seventies when I met Joy, my second wife, and subsequently married her, and had my daughter, Lucy, with Joy. We knew each other from about 1972 onwards, because Joy came to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Essex
{\*\xmlclose}, to the Department of Economics and we had a joint interest, because she was interested in the economics of smoking, and, I think, Tony Atkinson had appointed her. Tony was a friend of mine at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Essex
{\*\xmlclose}, and we came into contact at his instigation, if I remember correctly, when I went to meals with him and his wife, Judith, in the evenings at Brightlingsea. And this period is a period I don\rquote 
t like reflecting about much, personally, of uncertainty and self-doubts and -whether {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Essex{\*\xmlclose}
 was being a success anyway, or whether I was coming back to completing my work on poverty - it was a period of self-examination. I was a floater, I suppose, at that stage. I was somewhat unhappy, personally, very unhappy, personall
y, during that period, and yet clutching at straws.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 You\rquote re talking now about the mid-seventies?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Early seventies. I mentioned meeting Joy in 1971 or \rquote 
72. I was going backwards and forwards, literally, physically to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, to Ruth. A
nd then Ruth was very much involved with design and trying to make something of her life, now that all [the children] but Ben, were really reaching maturity. And then, I think she was looking for an excuse for getting away, as well as seizing an opportuni
ty to be away, by taking the Land-Rover abroad. And she\rquote 
d met people from overseas who she was attracted to, and, one way and another, it was possible for her to square the business of still being a mother for the youngest child, Ben, and seeking an adventu
re elsewhere, by taking him abroad for as long as a year.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Was this her attempt, really, to get out of the situation?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
It could be. It could have been. I think, like a lot of women in their late thirties, she must have been thinking, and was t
hinking of what she was going to do with her life now that her children were growing up, because at the time we parted, it has to be remembered that Matthew and Adam were 22 and 21, respectively. And Christian was 16/17. So, inevitably, Ruth, at one of th
e richest and most aware periods of life, was thinking of new things in different ways. And, I suppose, didn\rquote t find what I was up to my neck in at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Colchester{\*\xmlclose}
, that much attractive. They were very cosmopolitan. My sons have been extraordinarily cosmopol
itan in their attitudes since. I remember Ruth always speaking about my father as being provincial, and I think that symbolises one way in which personal relations can break down, that I, through my experience, and not only my work, was much more, as it w
e
re, much more of an extrovert in social relations, having to be, and very well aware that, you know, there were lots of innovations which people in the so-called provinces can show their success over Londoners. I mean, you only have to think of Nick Park 
and Wallis and Grommet to appreciate that kind of thing, who, of course, are in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. That kind of point. But so many people, in their own lives, do tend to reflect the place where they\rquote ve lived most of the time, and I think a lot of Londoners are that way inclined, and I\rquote 
m just saying that it seems to me that Ruth, and even my sons to a certain extent, reflected that during this period, at least. So that was one factor in a break-up which came about in 1974.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 What do you think was the best thing about your marriage with Ruth?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
The last year or two were pretty unhappy for both of us, but it did go for 25 years, and - I must have gained ... I think it\rquote s very difficult to not speak individually like this, that it\rquote s what I gained, compar
ed with what Ruth gained. She has every right to say much the same. I think she would say a lot about motherhood and her sons. I would, too, say a lot about fatherhood and my sons. And that sealed a very romantic love affair that we had at the beginning, 
a
t the age of 17. And, I suppose, I was looking to individual development to such an extent in those early years, that having the security and the satisfaction, and the fulfilment of family life, was enormously satisfying. It gave me a base from which I co
uld do other things, despite some of the handicaps I\rquote d suffered from in my origins, let\rquote 
s put it that way. I was lucky, enormously lucky, to have had someone like Ruth to give that form of security and basis for family existence, certainly until the late sixties, until the mid-sixties. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid3890122 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
I think we then went through a bit of a half-existence for the best part of ten years, eight, nine years, and it\rquote s almost like discovering that if you share family, when family grow up, you\rquote ve got to share something else. And there\rquote 
s an element of that. I\rquote ve put it too crudely, but there was an element of that about it. There\rquote s also an element of when you meet very young, there\rquote s a sense in which you haven\rquote 
t quite experienced the other gender to the extent that you can, or will. And we had met each other very young, in a very na\'efve, early part of our lives, and whether we\rquote 
d have chosen each other in any mature sense at the age of 25 or 35, is another matter. But that\rquote s what happened. And I\rquote m trying to say something about whether marriage should be forever or not. And I\rquote m saying, \'93No, it doesn
\rquote t have to be\'94. Sometimes marriages are matters of chance, matters of the moment, or the year, and they can be honoured and appreciated. And yet there has to be a different marriage, or the
re can be, entirely successful, or even more successful, in my case more, in some senses, in terms of satisfaction as well as mutual involvement and concern that I have now with Jean. It\rquote s not easy, of course, when you\rquote 
re, as I am still, immersed in a very
 happy marriage, to then give any objective view about the preceding experience. So I think all I can do is say that we were very happy, in my opinion, for the first ten years of our lives together, partly because we got involved in different interests, o
r discovered that we were rather more different than we\rquote d thought we were, from each other. As I say, the last eight or ten years was one of, looking back now, drifting apart, although we pretended otherwise at the time.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Is there anything more to be said about your relationships with the children in that period?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
A lot to be said for the seventies. I look back on the seventies as, perhaps, the most uncomfortable, the unhappy period of my life. It was a period when I was struggling to pull together }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Poverty in the UK}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 . It was a period when one or two sons had gone through difficulties, as most children do in their teens. I was discovering that I hadn\rquote 
t been a very effective father, in relation to education, in the seventies, as I would have wished to be. What else? The moment of glorious happiness with the arrival of Lucy in 1976.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
I was wondering whether in that phase of being a commuting father, whether you were aware of distancing going on or not?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 I supp
ose it came to each of us becoming conscious and exchanging the information with each other, in making our own lives. Ruth was making her own life, up to a point, with design, and the mentor of that, Robert Wetmore, for example. Discovering the appeal of 
travel, and other cultures.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
But with the boys, you were seeing them much less. Do you feel that you were drifting away a bit from them, or not?
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid5648674 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Oh yes. I was saying that I\rquote ve regretted not being more [involved] on a day-to-day basis of their experiences at school, and not only at school, in sport and everything else. I\rquote 
d endeavoured to play a part, you know, Speech Days, and attending performances of one sort and another, whether in plays or singing at the school, and catching up, but still with story time. You\rquote 
ve got to remember, part of the problem of this is keeping as much in tune with sons of a wide span of age. It\rquote s not always easy, when you\rquote ve got four, to be telling one a story, Ben, maybe, and yet engaging with the girlfriends of the e
ldest, and trying to show interest and take pleasure in what they tell you, what he tells you about it. And it\rquote s almost like saying that when you do have children of different ages, it\rquote s rather like siblings of different ages, that you can
\rquote t solve the problem by spending time all together in one place, on one Saturday or Sunday. It doesn\rquote t work like that. They\rquote ve got their other activities, and they\rquote 
re often out and about. So I think, yes, we did - drift apart is wrong, so much as we weren\rquote t together as oft
en as we should have been. Or, I would have liked to have been. And there were a huge number of events during this period, it was just a chaotically, intriguing and very full existence, certainly for me, and I think it was for them too. But our paths didn
\rquote t cross as far and as long-lasting as I would have wished.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 And then when you split with Ruth, how did that affect your relationship with the boys?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 I\rquote ve never forgotten the time when we had a disastrous meal once, Ruth got exasperated and thr
ew a plate across the room. And I think that, as is often the case here, the children, to some extent, blamed me, or to a large extent, and perhaps still do, one or two of them, for taking the decision to leave, because I did. I think that Ruth, despite h
aving made a different life, was wanting to keep the same base, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}Mansfield Place{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, I mean. And my sons - I suppose they didn\rquote 
t know quite what to think at first. I mean, I think they are generous in the sense that they felt that their father had met a different person, and was living in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Colchester{\*\xmlclose}. They knew too little about 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Colchester{\*\xmlclose}, which is a great sadness on my part. I wish they\rquote d experienced more of it. Ruth very rarely came. I can only remember her coming twice, all that time, in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Colchester{\*\xmlclose}. And that\rquote s my fault for not revealing that side of my life enough to my sons, never mind Ruth. So you can see, there\rquote 
s a lot of self-recrimination going on in this period, for me now, in talking about it. I don\rquote t deny that they blamed me at that period. They had the ear of their mother, and their mother, didn\rquote 
t release them enough after [they reached the age of] 18 or so, and maybe this event stopped them becoming as independent as I feel they might have become, two or three of them. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid5648674 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 That\rquote s another side to this kind of enterprise. You can
\rquote t really talk about a marriage without talking about the fall-out, as far as different members are concerned, and the fact that sons and daughters often find it very difficult to be impartial in any f
ull sense of that word, when something quite complicated has taken place. All that one can argue is that everybody in our kind of culture is encouraged to talk about blame when, in fact, it isn\rquote 
t blame so much as a very reasoned understanding of events and experiences and relationships, which one has to look for. It was almost as if there was a confirming aspect of this. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid5648674 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
There was certainly a period when I saw too little of them, and some of our meetings subsequently, which had to be individual rather tha
n collective, that was a problem for me, that catching up was difficult. And, after all, during this period, I was then beginning more and more to feel an obligation to my mother, who was becoming old and increasingly confined to the house, and I adopted 
t
he practice of coming to see her regularly once a week, and sometimes tried to combine it with seeing one or other of my sons. But my life had to be, or was increasingly becoming lodged in Colchester, despite my peripatetic campaigning and lecturing, and 
media activities, journeying up to London, but it was often journeying there and back from Colchester, rather than having an easy opportunity of staying with my sons, because they were living in their mother\rquote 
s house, in my former home, where I felt uneasy about returning to. I wasn\rquote t particularly welcome. There wasn\rquote t a bed in another room, to come back to. Yes, I did stay at my mother\rquote s, but my mother\rquote 
s was, basically, to all intents and purposes, two rooms, one of which was a kitchen. It did have a Put-U-U
p there, in a kind of old divan, and I existed on that sometimes, some nights, in order to see my sons. Many people would say, listening to this, or reading this, that it was a piece of very bad planning on my part. Well, it may have been. But then I was 
trying to square the circle, and trying to finance this family, as well as my life in Colchester, and it wasn\rquote t easy to do that, and have a pied-a-terre in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}London
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. I didn\rquote t have a pied-a-terre in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and it wasn\rquote t really possible at my mother\rquote 
s, although I did stay there sometimes. So combining visits to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 with occasions when I could comfortably get to know my sons again for an afternoon, an evening, a day, this was not what I did, and which I wish I had made more of an objective.
