\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid5648674 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
It was wonderful, life with Lucy, and for me, it was a great new adventure, having a daughter. And it was also like a second chance at being a father. Compared with the fifties, the world ha
d moved on dramatically, and from the mid-seventies, or early seventies onwards, there were big changes taking place in the acceptance of responsibilities by fathers, and I remember Joy and I had an arrangement of, at weekends, I would take over, one day,
 the domestic work and looking after Lucy, while she did her professional work, and catching up on correspondence, as she wanted to do as an economist. And she did the next day. We had that, and I think, quite genuinely, for the first four years of Lucy
\rquote s l
ife, I did as much in her upbringing, physically, as Joy did. And I take great pleasure in that, of course. And that applies to putting her to bed, and getting up, and finding a cot and painting a cot, and doing the nappies, and taking her to day-nursery,
 and bringing her back from day-nursery. We had a day-nursery at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Colchester{\*\xmlclose}, partly at my instigation, I may tell you, but more coincidentally than to suit my own personal needs, I may say! (LAUGHS) 

\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid5648674 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 However, we shared the upbringing of Lucy until, in
 1980, I met Jean, and really appreciated that I had made quite a big mistake in the 1970s, and that I\rquote d now met the person who meant most to me in my entire experience.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Would you say that the marriage was already in a rather difficult state when you met Jean? 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Oh yes. It\rquote s difficult to say this, isn\rquote t it. I think all husbands and wi
ves keep to themselves deep questions about the success of partnerships, and obviously, many of us, most people romanticise what partnership or marriage should be all about, in the early stages, and are not realistic enough about what it means to be toget
her, while yet pursuing their own individual interests. It\rquote s that kind of issue which is big. Maybe I it was too early for me to have got committed again so quickly to another family. But it happened.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 What were the good things about that marriage to Joy?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
I suppose it was me discovering I could take a more responsible role, play a more responsible role. I mean, if you\rquote re asking from my point of view - from Joy\rquote s point of view, you\rquote 
d have to ask her - from my point of view, it was that, here was I, able to play a more responsible family role than I\rquote 
d been able to do, certainly, during the sixties with Ruth. And a more effective one, and a more well-regarded one, I think, is true, and accepted. Joy was an economist, and, therefore, professionally,
 we had more in common in understanding what demands were being thrown at both of us by a university. And so, compared with Ruth, here was somebody who understood the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Colchester{\*\xmlclose}
 situation, and not only the local situation, also the academic and professional situation, which was easier. It meant you had more things to talk about in common.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Did you share intellectual interests?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Up to a point, yes, because, as I\rquote 
ve said already, Joy was interested in the economics of tobacco and smoking, an
d we shared this knowledge, scientific knowledge, about the desirability of not smoking, which is still having ramifications all round the world. And that gave us a kind of common concern, which was pretty important. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid5648674 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 I suppose I - I was going to say I wa
s blind to certain things about our relationship. I blinded myself to certain things about our relationship, because I just didn\rquote 
t want to think about where this was leading to, or whether it was the right personal basis for both of us for a long partnership. And it\rquote 
s very difficult to explain these things. People at the University must have blamed me for suddenly having a young child, and then suddenly, for the second time, leaving my wife. And all I can say is that these things are not always easy to comp
rehend, on the part of others. All I can say is, I had an overwhelming sense of relief that a pretence, and I don\rquote 
t mean this in any bad sense, was, could be, abandoned. But I was pretending to a happy family life, when, I suppose, in my innermost being, I knew it wouldn\rquote 
t work. Others said at the time, I should have known better, and should have resisted these other claims, but all I can say is that - in my mature consciousness, this was the first time I\rquote d really experienced real love.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 When you met Jean?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 When I met Jean, yes. 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Just before we leave ... In practical terms, though, you\rquote 
ve talked about how you were able to share as a father. Were you equally involved in other sides of domestic life? Cooking and cleaning and those sort of things?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Oh yes. Oh yes. I think I did more cooking than Joy did. I think that apart from the occasional Sunday lunch, which she made a great thing of, she would not claim that she was a versatile cook. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par So what you\rquote re saying is that it was more a question of personalities?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Yes. We had a child, and I loved having that child, but it [happened] almost before we had come to terms with who each other was. At least, that\rquote s my [memory] - yes, people see things differently, obviously, and t
hey think back to the past differently. I may not always have let on how I felt, and my reservations. I\rquote 
d got used to, in the University setting, of riding difficulties, and knew the value of taking a positive outlook, so that things would come right. And this affects personal life too. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid5648674 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
There were a lot of things which were continuing to distress me after parting from Hampstead, and my sons. I mean, there was that that was distressing, that somehow I couldn\rquote t rediscover the right kind of relationship, and
 I felt uneasy, in some senses, I\rquote ve not served myself well in how I handled that, and ought not to have allowed too much of a gap to grow. You know, it\rquote 
s often a great mistake, for all of us, when something goes wrong, and yet we want to maintain relations with others affected in the relationship, who have no part in it, I mean, I\rquote 
m talking about children here, when a marriage breaks up. It is extraordinarily important for the father to be allowed access, as well as to have access, and to make access for himself, and to know that that\rquote 
s important, because otherwise, if too much of a gap is allowed to grow, you can\rquote t recover it. There\rquote s a period of life which is a kind of silence, which is very difficult ... Yes, we know that children who don\rquote t discover who 
their real father or mother was until an advanced age, they can suddenly, the drive is there to rediscover. Yes, I can experience that, and I needed to experience that with my sons. And I\rquote 
m, with difficulty, hoping to do that now, and have been trying to do that for the last few years. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid5648674 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
But it also applied to my father, earlier, who, thanks to Jean, I got to know after 1980, after a long period when, predominantly [with] Ruth, but then also with Joy, [he] had been banished to the sidelines. So I\rquote m deliberately saying, \'93Look, it
\rquote s not just my sons and the difficulty of restoring, or continuing\'94, because it\rquote s `continuing' that is the most important word here, \'93continuing the relationship if it can be, and it\rquote s desperately important to do so\'94
. And I wish I\rquote d done more of that, yes. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid5648674 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
But I think Joy had her difficulties with her family too, and I hadn\rquote t realised how many, to be honest, when I first got to know her. I was a bit of the
 superior sociologist, who thought he could overcome most familial problems. A bit too optimistic about it all. And there was that side of it, her vulnerability to self-doubt about her family, which I tried to, not overcome, but tried to help her to manag
e better. I felt I was trying to carry things which were more than were going to prove possible. That\rquote s what I felt very deeply, and tried not to think about it for years. We weren\rquote 
t together very long, it was only four years, after all, thereabouts. But it\rquote s like one does in life, when you\rquote 
re leading a very busy life, as I was in the late seventies, in the preliminaries up to publishing a big work, and engaged in a hell of a lot of activities with Child Poverty Action Group, etc., Labour Party, Fabian Society, I didn\rquote 
t have to think about it much, so I didn\rquote t.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 I think you\rquote ve said sometimes that you actually drifted into that marriage. Is that so?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Yes, I suppose it was a consolation to me in the early seventies. Here was somebody who appreciate
d me being around, and I was there in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Colchester{\*\xmlclose}
, and there were occasions for meeting, anyway, through University life. Yes, you can say that I did. People can blame me for it, I can blame myself. [But] it was one of those things that materialised, p
artly because of a kind of loneliness one felt in a town, which wasn\rquote 
t a very sociable town anyway, and in a university which had been going through hell over the disruptions of, first, 1968, which continued with the graffiti period. It really continued for three or four, well, you know this, several years. So it wasn
\rquote t exactly a kind of comfortable place to be in of an evening, you know that. And the town wasn\rquote t either. And, therefore, evenings out and beginnings of a romance or two, were comforting.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 After the break up what happened to your relationship with Lucy?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
That was the worst thing about my excitement with Jean. I could go on at length about that excitement. It was for me, an unrivalled period of ecstasy. But it was tarnished, or colou
red by this agony, because it was an agony, of somehow having to disengage, not from Joy so much, as from everyday events with Lucy. And Joy didn\rquote 
t want to speak to Jean, and it was a terrible job to try to obtain access. And when I did obtain access, it w
as through a very stiff, uncomprehending and unsympathetic welfare officer, through the courts, who gave grudging terms of access, so that, effectively, I got to coming up to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}
 to collect Lucy, [going to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}] and taking her back to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose} from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}
Bristol{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And that didn\rquote 
t materialise for some time. I was allowed to see Lucy on a few occasions before this occasional fortnightly or monthly access was allowed over the weekend. And I just tried to make the best of it. Jean seemed to un
derstand much better than Joy did, what might be helpful to Lucy during this experience, in all sorts of ways, even to minor things like, well, not minor, she used to knit and make dresses for Lucy, for example. And if Lucy took them home, they\rquote 
d be lost or destroyed, or things wouldn\rquote t come back. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid5648674 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
There are many people, many couples, who have had this separation or divorce, who have these problems of access, and I think we\rquote re beginning to learn from reports, research, enquiries, media discussion, that fat
hers have often been left out in the cold in this process, even when they want to play a concerned and responsible part in their children\rquote s upbringing, and see them as much as they can. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid5648674 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 I think Lucy has survived. I mean, to this day, Lucy doesn
\rquote t easily talk about her mother to me, or about me to her mother. She has learnt to keep her life with her parents in two distinct compartments, and I think she will admit this, and talk, well, she\rquote 
d talk about that in the round, in the general terms. But it is some
thing very hard for a child to overcome. I had the distress, because it was a distress, of Lucy being taken away from primary school at Parliament Hill Fields, to go to a private school. And, given all my beliefs, I thought this was wrong. In the event, L
ucy has decided it was wrong, and yet she understands her mother, and is extraordinarily broad-minded and tolerant of both her parents in this situation. I think she\rquote s risen above this remarkably. But, you can imagine, I\rquote 
ve given you just a couple of instances, these are small examples, but the business about clothes, the business about the school, where there was a great division between myself and Lucy\rquote s mother. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid5648674 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
These things are not easy to survive, in terms of the threat they mean for one\rquote s present relationship. But I\rquote 
m saying that partly because of her own experiences, Jean responded with warmth, not only understanding. And I think it demonstrated what a stepmother could be like, and we have to face the fact that stepmothers and stepfathers are sometime
s precious additions to somebody\rquote s experience, and not merely alternatives.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 And so you have regular contact with Lucy now?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Yes. Lucy completed a History of Art course at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Manchester{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and I went up to see her some days. All along, in her adult phase, she has come to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Bristol
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} here, home, for weekends, and we\rquote ve got to know each other, or continued to know each other extremely well. She\rquote s now got a job in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}
Westminster{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, and this means we can now see each other for the occasional evening as well as lunch, at least once or twice a week, which is wonderful from my point of view. Which I do - I\rquote 
m probably seeing her tomorrow evening, having a meal with her.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 So you have more to do with her than any of the boys?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Yes. It\rquote 
s a two-sided thing, we have to understand. On the one hand, I was either prevented from having frequent associations with them, or finding it difficult, it\rquote 
s both, to have frequent associations with them, partly because I was looking after my mother
, who died at 93, three years go, but also my daughter was still in the growing up phase until not so long ago, till three or four years ago, and I needed to see her, because she was in that developmental stage, childhood stage. So when you try and find t
ime for them on a regular weekly basis, it\rquote 
s not easy then to make sure, as you would want, to have relations with the others, especially when Ben went to Ireland, a far-flung corner of Ireland. And one or two others of them, depending on the time we\rquote re speaking of, the year we\rquote 
re speaking of, were in Mansfield Place, where their mother resided, and were not eager to see me. I think that\rquote s fair. They were not eager. Either through Ruth\rquote s advice, or their own opinion, that was so. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid5648674 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 And I\rquote m just grateful for 
the chance, recently, to have been rebuilding chances of meeting, partly because we\rquote 
ve, recently, thinking of prospective future years of retirement, because of our love of Ireland, Jean and I have been there every year for the last ten, eleven years, we\rquote v
e finally found a marvellous little cottage in the mountains, an hour and a half\rquote s drive from where Ben lives. So this year, because we moved there last Spring, in the Spring of 1998, we\rquote ve seen a bit more of him on the occasions we\rquote 
ve been over, and we hope that will continue. Also, now that Ruth has moved, herself, although nearby in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Ireland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, it means that my relations with both [my older sons], especially Adam, but also Matthew, and continuingly Christian, have been a bit easier to foment.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 And what\rquote s happened to Joy?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Joy is still in the house she moved into after we separated, in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname PlaceName}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Kentish{\*\xmlclose} {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname PlaceType}}Town{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, where Lucy stays quite frequently still, before she sets up a home of her own. She\rquote s working from there
 now. And Joy hasn\rquote t remarried, though she\rquote s had a very close friend for some years.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 You obviously had a difficult divorce, but did you re-establish better contact later?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Yes, I find that it\rquote s easier to talk over the phone with Joy than with Ruth.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Could you tell me about meeting Jean?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Yes. This was 1980, Labour Party Conference, to which I\rquote 
d been invited to give a lecture, and attend a meeting or two. I responded to a luncheon invitation from Tony Benn, and at the other end of the table, my eye was caught by a young woman, who turned out to be Jean. And I think that it\rquote 
s one of those extraordinary occasions that not many people have the luck to experience, of love at first sight. We talked, the next day, about having coffee together, and then went to - I think the Labour Party Organisers\rquote  Dance...
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid5648674 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
I was saying, we met on this end of September day, September 28th, I think it was, and saw each other a lot during those next two or three days. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid5648674 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Jean was one of the key 
