ereabouts, and broke both his legs, and was paralysed from the waist down. She continued to look after the children. They were half way to separating then, and separated subsequently. So she was a lone parent between 1976 and 1980ish. She was an extraordi
narily domesticated and committed person, with high skills at cooking and needlework. To this day, she\rquote s making an extraordinary quilt of knitted white squares, which can\rquote t be made by machine, not yet, anyway. And made all her daughter
\rquote s dresses and so fort
h, and did the same when Lucy, my daughter, was young. And yet was making her way as an organiser in Labour Party politics. And we met and - I - in effect, left Joy that Christmas. I was so sure of our relationship. It was a very difficult Christmas, as y
ou can imagine. However, I went to join Jean in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}South Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Taunton
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, where we lived for about a year. I commuted to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, believe it or not, it was a long five hour commute.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 To {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Essex{\*\xmlclose}?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 To Essex, sorry, not to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}, to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Colchester{\*\xmlclose}. And did my best to arrive there, having got up at five o\rquote clock in the morning, or whatever, to get there by 11 o\rquote 
clock in the morning on a Monday, and I did my job teaching and so forth, and yet tried to fit in, as b
est I could, by returning to Taunton on a Friday, or even a Thursday night sometimes. And during that period, by chance, I heard from David Donnison, going back to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}London{\*\xmlclose}
 on the train from Colchester, that {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose} was looking for the replacement of Roy Parker as Head of the Department of Social Policy at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. I might not have chosen that, had I been confronted with other choices, but that seemed ideal in personal terms. It also meant that, in some senses, it was an expression of gender 
equality, because it\rquote s still quite rare that a husband goes to join his wife, for occupational reasons, rather than the other way round. And so I agreed to an appointment at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname 
place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Could I ask you just to give a picture of Jean as a person?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
A picture of Jean. I was saying that Jean had a lot of manipulable skills with her hands. She had learned, the hard way, to become an extremely good organiser, and, theref
ore, thinks very well about planning family timetables as well as professional ones. She\rquote 
s very good about narrative, far better than you and I. She remembers not merely events, but what was actually said. She has an extraordinarily retentive and direct memory. She will usually know any phone number that she\rquote 
s even used once or twice. She has a directness and a speed of absorption, which I find very impressive. It\rquote s very difficult to explain her personality without conveying at least a little about her acti
vities. And I was saying earlier that she left school at 16. When her daughter became a doctor, and her son became a teacher, long after I first knew them, I\rquote 
m talking about the late eighties after we were together, from 1980 - and we got married in 1985, in January 1985 - when her son and her daughter became teacher and doctor respectively, then she said, \'93Well, it may be my turn now\'94. And I\rquote 
m glad to say I was very enthusiastic about her going back to university, or going to university, rather. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid5648674 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 She\rquote d ta
ken one or two courses at the Open University during her work for the Labour Party, after her children were very young, and yet she decided she\rquote 
d like to read law. She read law very successfully at the London School of Economics, and became a barrister tow
ards the end of the eighties, and was approached out of the blue, to be a candidate for the Labour Party, for Bristol East Constituency in 1992. And she agreed, and was not only elected at the first round locally, to be the candidate, but also elected at 
t
he subsequent election. Her two predecessors, having been Tory MPs, the first of whom, the first time, had displaced Tony Benn in 1983, I think it was, and she had a majority of two and a half thousand, which, at this latest election in 1997, became a maj
ority of sixteen and a half thousand. So these are activities which she handles extraordinarily well. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid5648674 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 She\rquote 
s someone who can get on with people at different levels, partly because of her working-class background made good in professional ways, both as a la
wyer and as an organiser, and then as MP. I find it quite remarkable how well she can get on with so many people, and yet engage with them in a more detailed and serious and, let\rquote 
s say, direct way, than I find myself capable of doing, in the sense that she can recollect occasions of acquaintance and what happened, and who said what, in ways which make others very warmly responsive. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid5648674 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Her commitment, as a person, to the best things is something that I never tire of warming to. I mean she\rquote ll care as much abou
t Kay, the person who helps us in the home, and her different set of relationships, as she will about David Blunkett, who she\rquote s working with at the moment in Parliament. There\rquote s not even unconscious status seeking. She\rquote 
ll give as much time to the person wh
o gives her coffee in the restaurants. Tony Blair, and, indeed, she has meetings with Tony Blair, because of her position in the Parliamentary Labour Committee, every week. And I know, from the way she approaches that, and the way she talks about that, th
at it\rquote s given as much importance, and equal importance, as a meeting in her constituency with a Pakistani male who\rquote s having problems about getting his wife into England. And she\rquote 
ll give as much time, and equal time, and equal concern to that. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid5648674 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 And I suppose that\rquote 
s an aspect of her humanity, which I find quite stunningly attractive. I never thought I could get on with someone of the other sex quite so unselfconsciously. I suppose I\rquote m self-conscious a lot because I\rquote 
m guilty about not doing things I should be doing, and I\rquote m a bit awkward at times, and forgetful. Yet there\rquote 
s an ease and a sort of relaxation about our acquaintance, which is, I know from experience of a lot of others, quite unusual, and very rarely argumentative, although I\rquote m sometimes rather more obstinate than she is, that I\rquote 
m right about something! But there is a forbearance on her part for idiosyncrasies as well as interest, and yet I welcome this homeliness, this routine, this width of interest that she\rquote s given me. That\rquote s quite a lot, to be ho
nest, in tribute to anyone.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
