, it just seems the opportunity never arises. But MPs have to go to votes at seven o\rquote clock and ten o\rquote clock, usually, that\rquote s the normal routine, and, as you can understand, it\rquote s not easy to fit in going to see }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 The Barber of Seville}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858  in between whiles!
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Through getting together with Jean, you became a stepfather. Can you say something about that experience?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Important question. Her two children, David and Sarah. Sarah is the older of the two. When I first knew them in 1980, then they were, I suppose, 1980, let\rquote s work it out quickly. David was about 11 or 12, Sarah was about 14. Let\rquote 
s say that they were at a rather difficult stage! I remember David went through that phase, as everybody will recall with their own children, of having zips on. He had a pair of black trousers with about - he was quite good at sewing, actually, and using
 a sewing machine, and I think he had about 35 zips on his trousers, which he loved very much! He also had live worms, as bait, in plastic bowls, which he tended to keep under his bed, or in the drawer of the cabinet. And, believe me, that was no pleasant
 
sight when they got loose! (LAUGHS) And I think that conveys something of my initial experience of him. And Sarah was showing great generalist talent at acting and singing, and she was good at gymnastics, and was told, at first, that she ought to be a nur
se, by her senior teachers. And Jean said, \'93Why the hell shouldn\rquote t she consider being a doctor?\'94 And that stirred the school up somewhat. And in the end, she did become a doctor. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid5648674 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
But I went through a lot - through Jean and my consciousness of meeting the 
children, though obviously I saw less of them than did Jean - I think they were uneasy about me. They were happy with me, but also uneasy with me at the beginning, and I think this is pretty common. I mean, they were happy with me at the beginning, becaus
e I was a source of considerable pleasure through the local supermarket, because when I came on a Friday night, we used to go bundling off to the local Sainsbury\rquote 
s, or Safeways, and I would try to treat everybody, you see. So I was the source of jam tarts a
nd treacle pudding, and liquorice allsorts, or whatever, and they thought this was terrific, because Jean had been through a period of penury as a lone parent, may I point out, and trying to earn a bit of a living, part-time, as a local Constituency, and 
then Regional Assistant Organiser. So I was, you know, I was a bit like a glad hander to them, in some senses. But also, of course, feeling a bit critical about them, because they weren\rquote 
t my children, and, of course, if children are not your children, you\rquote re not quite as indulgent or forgiving, or sympathetic, on the whole. But I quickly learned that David had a kind of inventiveness that I hadn\rquote 
t appreciated in him, or he had, to a greater extent than any of my sons, my own direct sons. And Sarah had a kind
 of professional calm and organisation, which was quite remarkable. So there were things to admire and welcome, in both of them, from which, in a way, I could learn, and share with Jean. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11749505 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
I felt uneasy about calling them a son or a daughter, particularly since Chris is very much alive, and lives nearby in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Taunton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, Jean\rquote 
s former husband. And I\rquote m glad to say, Jean and her former husband have amicable relations, and both son and daughter have a totally respectful interest in the lives of each of their parents, which is encouraged by the parents, which isn\rquote 
t that common. And I suppose I benefit from that, because you can then see, when that happens, that if the parents are able to handle that themselves, the incoming step-parent, as I was, hasn\rquote t got s
o many problems, and can actually give more, instead of trying to fend off some of the animosity, can actually share in some of the joint activity more. And I think that rubs off on the children, too.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 So would you not have really taken the role of a father, in the sense of discipline?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Oh, I didn\rquote 
t have to, because they were both of an age where, well, discipline ... I mean, take the youngest. I think Sarah was very much her own person by the time I first knew her. She was well into her teens, let\rquote 
s put it that way, very much leading a busy and extrovert life, and I wasn\rquote t there a lot anyway, because I was a commuter and a peripatetic at first, coming from as far away as Colchester. And then when I joined them in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}Taunton{\*\xmlclose}, I was forever going up and down the railway line, or the road, to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, to do my full-time teaching. That was from the beginning of 1982, remember. So I wasn\rquote t on the spot enough to really have much, or need to have much dealing in that way with Sarah. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11749505 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 With Da
vid, he was younger, yes. But, frankly, coming in as a stepfather, I was very diffident, and I think it was right to be diffident. He was still kind of trying to come to terms with the separation of his mother and father, even though that had occurred fou
r years before I arrived on the scene. And perhaps he\rquote 
d got used to being with his mother and having her, as it were, giving direct attentions to him, before I came on the scene, and had got that well-established. So I think there were senses in which he almost resented my materialisation. He\rquote 
s never really conveyed that. It was just, really, in the way in which he had a somewhat curt and unengaged manner, which may have been the result of, rather than the condition for the distance between us. But we got on
 well enough. Just to give an example of this, I\rquote d always loved cricket when I was young, well into adulthood, and he\rquote 
s an extremely good cricketer, and we just took great delight in throwing a tennis ball, or a cricket ball, hard at each other, and giving
 each of us the hardest job of catching the ball. We took delight in trying to make the other one drop it. And we took delight, too - Jean had a dog called Arrow, who was only a puppy when I first met her, and this sort of cemented relations with the step
children, we had this dog around whom a lot of activities could be built, and shared responsibilities could be found. And I tended to become very much the, almost the predominant, later on, predominant carer of Arrow the dog, as I did when we came to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} and lived first of all in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}Ashley Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
?
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 That\rquote s in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}St. Paul
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}\rquote s?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 That\rquote s right, yes. Perhaps I should have recounted this very briefly, that 1980, Jean and I spent in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}South Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Taunton{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. We then moved to 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}Ashley Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, partly out of choice, that I was always keen on professionals working in inner city areas where they tended to float in and float out, and I tried to work there for a few years. We found it diff
icult to do that. We were there three and a half years, or thereabouts, before we went to Brixton in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, for two years, because of Jean\rquote 
s job, that was in the mid-eighties. But between 1981 and 1984, inclusive, we were in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}Ashley Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, which was the centre of the riots that took place in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}St. Paul{\*\xmlclose}\rquote s in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 in 1980, just before we went there. So part of that experience of being in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}Ashley Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, was coming to terms with living in an inner city area, with a 
lot of abrasive feeling. And we did our best, and both of us played a part locally. I became a governor of the primary school, for example, and yet it became very difficult for Jean and Sarah to continue this, because I suddenly found, I noted that neithe
r of them went out in the evening after seven o\rquote clock, and they just felt they couldn\rquote t, because of the area and it\rquote s seedy side. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11749505 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
And then I was mugged one night, taking Arrow out. I was lucky that the police happened to be around the corner on another in
cident, and the three who were kicking me, and trying to - I presume they were about to get my wallet, just ran off, because it seemed the police would be coming round the corner. And that was a slightly upsetting experience. Some people would say I
\rquote d be crazy to go out at 11 o\rquote 
clock at night with a dog, for a walk in the surrounding streets. But, so be it. And, but more to the point, we were burgled three or four times in the last year and a half, and one of those occasions was really quite frightening, wh
en Jean was in the house. It was a tall house, two rooms, one above another, from the basement, if you include the basement, five storeys.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 A Georgian terraced house?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
Yes. Very nice terrace. And it had been done up. One of those houses which can either almost become a squat, but also, if properly renovated, can shine like one of those Georgian or Queen Anne era homes. And Jean was up on the top floor, when she was dist
urbed by noises below. And when she went to the head of the stairs above the room where she\rquote 
d heard the noises - and then [the burglar] came out and fled down the stairs and out of the house with his companion, who was downstairs. And subsequently [she] found that they\rquote d broken open the basement door with a spade, they\rquote 
d smashed it open, because it was too securely locked to break in easily. And they\rquote d put the television sets and usual technical stuff, ready on each of the landings already, to be rushed out. It was only because they didn\rquote 
t realise somebody was in the house that that had happened. But, as you can imagine, that was rather upsetting, and I think it undermined our confidence in living, or returning to that area, after we spent our couple of years in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}London{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} when Jean went, in her {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname Street}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname address}}Walworth Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 experiment, and found it wanting, and decided to become a law student. And when we came back, we were, I think, wanting to go from one extreme to the other, from the inner city to the pl
easant, more than suburban home, country home, really, to try that, because that stemmed a bit from her childhood, and my romantic visions of some of the years I\rquote 
d spent in North Yorkshire. And we were very lucky finding a cottage not far off the motorway, North of Bristol, which is where we are now. And so that\rquote s been the case since 1987, we\rquote ve been there for 12 years now. Eleven, nearly 12.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 So this was originally a farm labourers cottage?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Yes. We\rquote re lucky enough to know very well one of the
 workers on the local farm, John, who, in his spare time, helps us with the garden, because it\rquote s quite a big garden. He\rquote 
s a great fund of information about the countryside, and knowledge, and tremendous. And we have a photograph of him in his mother\rquote s arms, in this house, and that\rquote 
s why he particularly likes coming here, because he was here for a few years in his early years. And we\rquote re told there was usually not just a family to a cottage, but a family to each room in the cottage! And this is, we\rquote ve had a b
it built on, but it\rquote s basically two rooms up, and two rooms down, with a kitchen, or scullery, etc., attached. And it\rquote 
s got a basement cellar, small cellar. And we know, in fact, we know more about the cottage further along this lane, where two cottages ha
ve been knocked together, and which are now occupied by a couple, but which were then occupied by, I think, six families. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11749505 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
And these were the rural underclass, because this was a very large estate, and back in the 1930s, farming began to change, and there
 began to be the first signs of mechanisation. Numbers on the farms, and workers around different farms were being reduced, and this was the least sought after area, because it was the furthest ... these few cottages, were the furthest from the road where
 the buses ran, or access to the local shop was. There was a local shop, well, half a mile away, let\rquote 
s put it that way. And the farmers tended to assign their most temporary and least wanted workers here, giving the more desirable rented cottages to their l
oyal, long-lasting workers elsewhere. So these were the cottages which were sold off first, paradoxically! And it still is a kind of island, small island, within the estate, which has owner-occupiers on it now. One of them is a teacher.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 There is one
 last area, which I was hoping you might say something about, which is about your experience of getting older yourself. Would you like to reflect a little on that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Gosh! There are all sorts of ways of reflecting on this. I suppose, in a sense, I\rquote m 
grateful I did most of my work on ageing when I was young! I suppose I was a bit distant from ageing, and, therefore, I didn\rquote t have to declare an interest! (LAUGHS) I keep being tempted to make a return journey, because, of course, during life, it
\rquote s not merely that experience has taught something, which causes you to pick up those items which you missed out, or didn\rquote t get in the right priority, it\rquote s also that there is a kind of ... 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11749505 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
In reflecting about age here I am, 70, talking about ageing, which I wrote most about during my twenties and thirties, and it\rquote s almost as if there are three things from which I can gain in writing about the subject now. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11749505 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 There\rquote 
s self-knowledge, the experience of growing older and what that has taught you about the eternal experience of ageing that everybody experiences, that may be material and of interest. But then there\rquote s the experiences that you\rquote 
ve been exposed to, that give a somewhat more multidimensional view about ageing. But then, thirdly, there\rquote s the fact that ageing it
self has changed. That ageing for the generation I am in is different from the ageing that was experienced when I was young, and the ageing that our grandchildren are going to experience. So there\rquote 
s something of quite fundamental value in trying to convey those three ideas. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11749505 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
And I suppose one way of handling this, in personal terms, is to say, \'93Well, what about my twenties, my thirties, my forties, my fifties, sixties and seventies? If I look back, what is there that\rquote s useful to say about those particular 
experiences?\'94 I\rquote ve told a story where, in the 1970s, when I was in my forties and early fifties, that was really the most difficult and unhappy of my life. Now, is this unusual? I think not. There\rquote 
s the common or garden reference to middle life crisis. But I think men have that problem as much as women, in very different ways, and it\rquote s almost as if there\rquote 
s a sense of relief at bringing up children, and then becoming independent, and, therefore, you can literally confront new activities of a major kind, which you couldn\rquote t earlier. And there\rquote s also reflection on what the relationships you
\rquote ve had amount to, and there are those thoughts too. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11749505 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 And that\rquote s part of ageing, that you\rquote 
re suddenly made aware of the fact that you\rquote re not eternal. At some time during that period; [for] some people it doesn\rquote t occur to until later. In my case, I honestly didn\rquote 
t think about ageing, and in my own case, of thinking there was a limit to my life, I didn\rquote t really begin thinking about that until I was well into my fifties, which is a very odd thing to have to admit. It might sound extraordinarily na\'ef
ve, but I can\rquote t honestly remember any serious self-examination about how much longer there might be before I died. I didn't really think that until the last ten years or so, to be honest
. It was more or less as if, well, the decisions I took, the time I devoted, it hadn\rquote t got to be affected by, \'93Oh, will I be alive long enough to do this or that?\'94 None of that at all. That\rquote s one big reflection I have about ageing.

\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Do you think having a younger wife might have contributed to that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 There\rquote s a sense - I think it affects a lot of people, and I don\rquote 
t think that only applies to men, though it seems to, by virtue of their power, of the strings of control, that having a younger wife has been one way of postponing decisions about ageing, which many men have. What I\rquote m trying to suggest is that, it
\rquote s only because men have held the power, that they seem to have been most affected by that. I think, increasingly, as ... if women do, gain greater equality of power, that the boot will be on the other foot, and there will be occasions when men don
\rquote t mind, or allow themselves to marry older women. I think this is something of political and social creation. Well, I\rquote d value having the opportunity to spend a lot more time reflecting about that. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11749505 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
But I did marry, on the second occasion, but especially the third, my wife, Jean, is 14 years younger than me. I suppose sometimes I worry that I can be still active enough to be of some good to her. That d
oes matter to me. I think it matters to any person, in fact, whatever their age, but it obviously occurs to people who are older than their spouse, that kind of thought. But I suppose that confirms your question about being younger. It\rquote 
s even more important, it seems to me, to address the issue of retirement, than the question of age.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Can you talk about retirement?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Because I\rquote m one of those rare exceptions. I\rquote m privileged, really, to be able to say t
hat I retired from the University, nominally, on the 1st August, 1993. My full-time work for the University was complete, I\rquote 
d earned my pension, and from that date, I was expecting not merely to draw the pension, but to give up my full-time job as Head of the Department of Social Policy at the {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname PlaceType}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}
University{\*\xmlclose} of {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname PlaceName}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
, and I did so. But already, before that, I was one of those people who was doing quite a lot of research, I was teaching, I had a deep commitment in the overseas course, a 
Mastership programme which I had started, and I was lucky enough, because Bristol was strapped for cash at that time, employing an Emeritus Professor to go on doing a bit of teaching was not too bad, compared with appointing someone of that stature part-t
ime to do it. It would have been much more difficult. So I was lucky enough for four, or was it five, further years, to do that at {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname City}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Bristol{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And I
\rquote m now very lucky to be able to say, although it\rquote s not to the same regularity, I\rquote m doing quite a lot of
 occasional teaching on the M.Sc. programme at the London School of Economics, as Visiting Professor there, and I can, therefore, fit in, or keep going with some of the the different activities that I\rquote 
ve got into since that date of my formal retirement at 65. But I\rquote ve been privileged to be able to continue doing a lot of the things I was doing beforehand. So, retirement, in a way, doesn\rquote 
t apply so much to me, in the sense that my activities were transformed overnight, or quickly, because they haven\rquote t, to be
 honest. There have been new as well as old activities. So it causes me, though, to reflect on a much bigger issue. And I do honestly believe that this issue of the social institution of retirement, because it is a social institution, and I\rquote 
ve talked quite a lot to you about this, therefore I won\rquote 
t do more than be very compact now. But it seems to me that the social institutionalisation of retirement has been more important than the biological fact of ageing, and ought to be given much greater importance by
 those who discuss the matter, and try to foment individual as well as social answers to it in the future. 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11749505 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 I mean by that that we\rquote 
re experiencing something which is damaging, fundamentally damaging to society, which is the premature retirement of a lot o
f people, women as well as men, although men, hitherto, have been predominant, below the age of 65 and below the age of 60, and sometimes even as low as in their late forties, who are being pensioned off at great national cost, for insufficient reason, at
 
a time when many of them are still very active. And although many welcome it at the time, few of them continue to welcome it after the first two or three years, because it seems that retirement, and doing their garden, or doing some sketching or reading, 
and so on, will go on for the rest of their lives, many people find that it doesn\rquote t really fulfil them in the senses that society wants, or that they want, as individuals. And so, therefore, we\rquote 
ve got a major challenge of trying to reorganise our thinking a
bout paid and unpaid activities, and how we provide opportunities for partially-paid activities in particular, which give people a sense of social utility as well as a sense of individual fulfilment. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11749505 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 And I do think, I really seriously think, that the que
stion of retirement is far more serious and far more manageable, and far more practical to deal with than the problem of ageing. Yes, of course, I don\rquote 
t mean to imply that there is not a problem of ageing, there is for all of us, of how to accommodate the situations we find ourselves in, and one of those individual questions is not a question of just postponing survival. Because I don\rquote t think it
\rquote s a question of providing such comfortable surroundings that we can linger on in a kind of functionless role, that\rquote s attainable for more people. But there\rquote s no point in it for ourselves, unless we are, I don\rquote 
t know, enlarging ourselves in some, even if less generous way than we used to be doing.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 So in your own case, you\rquote re continuing as an academic. You\rquote re not
 thinking of taking up something completely new for this phase of your life?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 I haven\rquote 
t been. Jean and others sometimes suggest that I ought to think of taking up something new! (LAUGHS) Let\rquote s face it, a lot of people idly think of things they\rquote d love to do more of. I\rquote ve sometimes thought I\rquote 
d like to take up painting and sketching, that I did do in my youth, or writing fiction. Yes, I\rquote ve thought about those sort of things. But I suppose I\rquote m so attracted by the things that I\rquote ve been reasonably good at,
 that I can continue doing that I just get on with them. And so I am still doing a lot of the things that I used to do, which is writing, contributing to political debate, and currently doing some research. One assignment which I hope is going to take me 
to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname place}}Africa{\*\xmlclose} next year. But we\rquote ll see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 So what do you hope for most in the next few years?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 (LAUGHS) I would like to write at least two books that people will say they\rquote 
re worth returning to over the next 50 or 100 years. I think that would please me, if that proves to be possible. I\rquote d like to do that. I\rquote ve thought of one or two. There are several books, one or two of which are actually in the pipeline. 

\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11749505 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
But I suppose one which I would welcome as giving a more rounded idea of not only of what life I\rquote ve led, but how that would, perhaps, encourage others to think more about what kind of life they would like to lead. I suppose I\rquote 
d like to do that. Unfortunately, it is not yet the number one priority, but I have collected bits and pieces of it. I\rquote ve provisionally called it, \'93A Day in the Life of a University Teacher\'94
, and I would like to write a fairly substantial account of that kind. But as I\rquote ve said, or indicated already, partly, yes, an account of some of the more interesting things that have happened to me, but also it\rquote 
s intended to be more of a contribution to what a lot of people who\rquote ve led similar activities to me, do need to think about more.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Just to sum up, what would you say have been the worst and the best things in your life?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Worst and best? Mmm! My immediate reaction is to give you a split answer, but then that\rquote 
s partly the kind of life I\rquote ve led. Both on the worst and the best. I mean, the best: the expected answers are often in very personal terms in relation to the people you\rquote ve loved, or the people you\rquote 
ve lost. And my meeting with Jean, and my life with Jean, has been the best personal thing about my life. No question. But there are other best things! (LAUGHS) That all of us think about \endash  the birth of our sons and daugh
ters, the glorious memories, the images, the smells, the touch, of all that. That is magical, and you\rquote re just very glad to have been lucky enough to experience it, because not everybody can. Best and worst? 
\par 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11749505 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Worst? Often people talk of losing somebody ver
y close to them. I was an only child. I\rquote 
ve had the good fortune not to have lost any of my descendants yet, and I hope not to before I die. But, losing a mother, this affects many many, most, nearly all people. Losing a father. I suppose if you talk about 
worst moments, it would be difficult to escape thoughts about that, that\rquote s true. People who died too early, that is an awful worst moment, isn\rquote t it. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11749505 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
I talked about a split answer, because, quite seriously, to me, it\rquote s also worst in national/international
 terms, that I cannot but think of the gas chambers for the Jews, that played a repeated part in my conscious life, of being called back to it, just as now, yesterday, there was a fantastic - yesterday, speaking on the 1st February, 1999, on the 31st Janu
ary, there was a remarkably agonising film about the relations between a Serb, a Muslim and a Croat, and in the end, the Croat and the Serb, who were first-rate marksmen, were on opposing sides. And the Croat deliberately shot dead the Serb. Now, that
\rquote s only an example, but it would be almost like putting on blinkers if you talk about worst and best only in the family sense, and very close, because it\rquote s almost as if that\rquote s all that matters to us. And it doesn\rquote 
t. What matters to us is the most desperately awful events that you\rquote ve known in your lifetime, and, of course, you could add to that list. And what\rquote s so terrible is that some of the worst events are not those in distant memory, they\rquote 
re very very recent, and exist today, as in Kosovo today. 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11749505 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 So then you 
have to say best too, in those general terms. And it seems to me that we all have difficulty about acknowledging some of the periods and some of the developments that are wondrous. And there\rquote 
s something to be said about the management of egalitarian conditions of sociability, of community at different stages, of Scandinavian Socialism and the Welfare State. These egalitarians, you usually think of reservations about the best like that, don
\rquote t we? We don\rquote t talk so easily about the best international and socia
l events. We think of people, yes, we think of countries that are better. But best is a little bit elusive for us in terms of judging which features of this century are really things to be applauded and regarded fondly as methods of salvation or organisat
ion, and I suppose averting war can be among those things to be considered, which are not really very heavily publicised. And, therefore, that brings us back to examples like {\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname country-region}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns3{\factoidname 
place}}Northern Ireland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. You could argue some of the best things are like the delay, the putting off of the cataclysm of a war brought about between Unionists and Republicans. That\rquote s worth admiring.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \fi-1871\li1871\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin1871\itap0\pararsid11733749 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Paul:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Well, thank you, Peter, for a very thoughtful interview. Thank you very much.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid10294858\charrsid10294858 Peter:\tab }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 Thank you.
\par }\pard \ltrpar\s22\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid11749505 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11733749\charrsid10294858 
